{"title_page": "Scott Driscoll (linesman)", "text_new": "'''Scott Driscoll''' (born May 2, 1968, in [[Seaforth, Ontario]]) is a [[National Hockey League]] [[official (ice hockey)|linesman]], who wears uniform number 68.<ref name=\"nhl\">{{Cite web |url=http://nhlofficials.com/nhl-officials/view/11 |title=Scott Driscoll's profile |website=NHLOfficials.com |access-date=March 10, 2020 }}</ref> His career began in the [[1992-93 NHL season]]. He has worked more than 1,840 regular season games, 185 playoff games, three Stanley Cup Finals (2004, 2007, and 2014), and the 1996 World Cup of Hockey.<ref name=\"nhl\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Driscoll, Scott}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League officials]]\n\n{{Canada-icehockey-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Scott Driscoll''' (born May 2, 1968, in [[Seaforth, Ontario]]) is a [[National Hockey League]] [[official (ice hockey)|linesman]], who wears uniform number 68.<ref name=\"nhl\">{{Cite web |url=http://nhlofficials.com/nhl-officials/view/11 |title=Scott Driscoll's profile |website=NHLOfficials.com |access-date=March 10, 2020 }}</ref> His career began in the [[1992-93 NHL season]]. He has worked more than 1,840 regular season games, 185 playoff games, three Stanley Cup Finals (2004, 2007 and 2014) and the 1996 World Cup of Hockey.<ref name=\"nhl\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Driscoll, Scott}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League officials]]\n\n{{Canada-icehockey-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added commas", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scott_Driscoll_(linesman)"}
{"title_page": "Censorship of Facebook", "text_new": "{{See also|Internet censorship}}\n[[File:Facebook Logo (2019).svg|right|266px|[[Facebook]] logo]]Facebook has been replacing traditional media channels since its founding in 2003.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bozdag|first=Engin|date=2013-09-01|title=Bias in algorithmic filtering and personalization|journal=Ethics and Information Technology|language=en|volume=15|issue=3|pages=209\u2013227|doi=10.1007/s10676-013-9321-6|issn=1572-8439}}</ref> Censorship in the media, especially on Facebook is because of a variety of reasons, since Facebook accepts all kinds of content, with little or no moderation, and displays what people post publicly, this practice can sometimes threaten oppressive governments especially in totalitarian regimes while also propelling fake news, hate speech and misinformation thus undermining the credibility of online platforms and social media. Many countries have banned or temporarily limited access to the [[social networking website]] [[Facebook]], including [[Mainland China]],<ref name=\"chinablock\">{{cite web\n |title=China's Facebook Status: Blocked\n |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/theworldnewser/2009/07/chinas-facebook-status-blocked.html\n |date=July 8, 2009\n |publisher=ABC News9\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090711081856/http://blogs.abcnews.com/theworldnewser/2009/07/chinas-facebook-status-blocked.html\n |archivedate=2009-07-11\n }}</ref> [[Iran]],<ref name=\"iran and iraq\">{{cite web|accessdate=April 30, 2008|url=http://www.hamsaweb.org/crime/4.html|title=Facebook Faces Censorship in Iran|publisher=[[American Islamic Congress]]|date=August 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424001859/http://www.hamsaweb.org/crime/4.html#|archive-date=2008-04-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Syria]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-facebook-idUSOWE37285020071123|title=Syria blocks Facebook in Internet crackdown|date=2007-11-23|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-12-16|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201164617/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-facebook-idUSOWE37285020071123|archive-date=2019-12-01|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[North Korea]].<ref name=NK/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/this-is-how-kashmiris-are-using-facebook-twitter-despite-modi-govt-ban-on-social-media/357618/|title=This is how Kashmiris are using Facebook, Twitter despite Modi govt ban on social media|last=Javaid|first=Azaan|date=2020-02-01|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> Use of the website has also been restricted in various ways in other countries. As of May 2016, the only countries to ban access around the clock to the social networking site are China, Iran, Syria, and North Korea. However, since most North Korean residents have no access to the Internet,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/tech/north-koreas-internet-is-as-weird-as-you-think-it-is|title=North Korea's internet is as weird as you think it is|date=9 November 2017|access-date=31 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531090225/https://www.foxnews.com/tech/north-koreas-internet-is-as-weird-as-you-think-it-is|archive-date=31 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> China and Iran are the only countries where access to Facebook is actively restricted in a wholesale manner.\n\n== Algorithmic Censorship ==\nOnline censorship by Facebook of algorithmic forms raises concerns including the surveillance of all instant communications and the use of machine learning systems with the [[Algorithmic bias|potential for errors and biases]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cobbe|first=Jennifer|date=2019-08-14|title=Algorithmic Censorship on Social Platforms: Power, Legitimacy, and Resistance|language=en|location=Rochester, NY|ssrn=3437304}}</ref> Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook\u2019s CEO and majority shareholder, published a memo on censorship. \u201cWhat should be the limits to what people can express?\u201d he asked. \u201cWhat content should be distributed and what should be blocked? Who should decide these policies and make enforcement decisions?\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2018/12/facebook-punish-censorship/577654/|title=The Speech That Facebook Plans to Punish|last=Friedersdorf|first=Conor|date=2018-12-11|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115132324/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2018/12/facebook-punish-censorship/577654/|archive-date=2019-11-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Facebook has been giving permission for instant removals of content and censoring what the public can see. An example of this is journalist [[Ford Fischer]] immediately being banned from posting content for 3 days as he \ntried to share an article about his censorship on YouTube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reclaimthenet.org/facebook-bans-ford-fischer-links/|title=Facebook bans journalist Ford Fischer from posting links as he attempted to share YouTube censorship article|date=2019-12-17|website=Reclaim The Net|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship by country==\n\n=== Austria ===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Austria}}\nLike France and Germany, Austria has laws prohibiting [[Holocaust denial]]. This caused 78 Facebook posts to be banned from the country in 2013.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://web-a-ebscohost-com.ezp.mesacc.edu/ehost/detail/detail?vid=43&sid=478b8a6a-822d-4e40-919b-f968207ac5cb%40sdc-v-sessmgr06&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d#AN=95955653&db=aph|title=Facebook Reveals Which Countries Censor Your Newsfeed|last=Stamper|first=Laura|date=2014-04-15|website=Time|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh===\n{{see also|Blasphemy law in Bangladesh}}\nBangladesh (like Iran, China and North Korea) had banned Facebook before - the Bangladeshi ban operated for a short period of time.{{when|date=April 2017}} The [[Awami League]]-led [[government of Bangladesh]] announced a countrywide ban on Facebook and other social-network websites. Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]] (in office from 2009) proposed the establishment of an [[Internet surveillance|Internet monitoring]] committee with the help of Bangladesh's intelligence services. Right-wing political parties and groups in Bangladesh protested against bloggers and others they had considered \"blasphemous\" at the time of the proposal. Extremists in the country had [[Attacks on secularists in Bangladesh|murdered eight secularists]], including atheist blogger [[Ahmed Rajib Haider]], who was fatally stabbed in February 2013. National riots over the country's war-crimes trials resulted in the deaths of 56 people between 19 January 2013 and 2 March 2013.\n\nOn 18 November 2015 the same Awami League government banned Facebook again on the eve of the final judgement of [[Bangladesh Jamaat-e-Islami]] leader Ali Ahsan Muhammad Mujahid and [[Bangladesh Nationalist Party]] leader Salauddin Kader Chowdhury. Both the politicians and previous minister have been issued a death sentence by the War Criminals Tribunal and the review board of the Supreme Court of Bangladesh has finally given their judgement in favour of the previously given one.\n\nThe Bangladesh government lifted the ban on 20 December 2015. Facebook is accessible in Bangladesh as of late 2017.\n\n===China===\n{{main|Internet censorship in China}}\n\n[[Internet censorship in the People's Republic of China|In China]], Facebook was blocked following the [[July 2009 \u00dcr\u00fcmqi riots]]  because [[East Turkestan independence movement|Xinjiang independence activists]] were using Facebook as part of their communications network, and Facebook denied giving the information of the terrorists.<ref>{{cite web|title= 80 pct of netizens agree China should punish Facebook|url= http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90776/90882/6697993.html|date= July 10, 2009|publisher= The [[People's Daily Online]]|accessdate= July 13, 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090714121501/http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90776/90882/6697993.html|archive-date= July 14, 2009|url-status= live}}</ref> Some Chinese users also believed that Facebook would not succeed in China after [[Google China]]'s [[Operation Aurora|problems]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Facebook\u4e0a\u6f14\u620f\u5267 \u7eb8\u8001\u864e\"\u975e\u6b7b\u4e0d\u53ef\"|url= http://blog.sina.com.cn/s/blog_000ed7d80100i79k.html|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131214040727/http://blog.sina.com.cn/s/blog_000ed7d80100i79k.html|archive-date= December 14, 2013|url-status= dead|access-date= December 10, 2013}}</ref> [[Renren]] (formerly ''Xiaonei'') has many features similar to Facebook, and complies with PRC Government regulations regarding content filtering.\n\nAs of 20 August 2013, there have been reports of Facebook being partially unblocked in China.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.headlineasia.com/facebook-and-twitter-in-china/ |title=Facebook And Twitter In China! |date=2013-08-20 |accessdate=2013-12-10 |website=Headline Asia |publisher=[[South China Morning Post]] |publication-date=2013-08-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212145054/http://www.headlineasia.com/facebook-and-twitter-in-china/ |archivedate=2013-12-12 }}</ref> However, according to the \"Blocked in China\" website, Facebook is still blocked as of December 7, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blockedinchina.net/?siteurl=facebook.com |title=Test If Any Website Is Blocked In China |website=BlockedInChina.net |accessdate=August 2, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129121311/http://www.blockedinchina.net/?siteurl=facebook.com |archive-date=January 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is not blocked in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]]. Facebook is currently working on a censorship project for China, where a third party would be allowed to regulate on Facebook and control popular stories that come around. This would be a huge attempt on Facebook to get back into China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.ezp.mesacc.edu/login?qurl=http://link.galegroup.com%2fapps%2fdoc%2fA474768520%2fITBC%3fu%3dmcc_mesa%26sid%3dITBC%26xid%3d9a60479f|title=Off-Campus eResource Access - Paul A. Elsner Library @ Mesa Community College|website=login.ezp.mesacc.edu|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n===Egypt===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Egypt}}\nblocked for a few days in [[Egypt]] during the [[2011 Egyptian protests]].<ref name=\"inaccessible in Egypt\">{{cite news\n| url=  https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jK3UhbzReiwvzyJImym-FEeZb87A?docId=CNG.737c6f9342ecee94153df06ff00b5617.a1\n| title=  Facebook reported inaccessible in Egypt\n| publisher=  [[Google]]/[[Agence France-Presse]]\n| date=  26 Jan 2011\n| accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\nLike Austria and Germany, France has laws prohibiting [[Holocaust denial]]. Because of this, a reported 80 Facebook posts were blocked from the French people in 2013.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Germany===\nIn July 2011, authorities in Germany began to discuss the prohibition of events organized on Facebook. The decision is based on numerous cases of overcrowding by people who were not originally invited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ptjornal.com/201107041737/mundo/alemanha-festas-convocadas-pelo-facebook-sao-ameaca-a-ordem-publica.html |title=Alemanha: Festas convocadas pelo Facebook s\u00e3o \"amea\u00e7a \u00e0 ordem p\u00fablica\"|publisher=Ptjornal.com|accessdate=October 29, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904145814/http://www.ptjornal.com/201107041737/mundo/alemanha-festas-convocadas-pelo-facebook-sao-ameaca-a-ordem-publica.html|archivedate=September 4, 2011}}<br/>{{cite web|url=http://www.destakjornal.com.br/readContent.aspx?id=10,101638|title=Alemanha pode proibir festas combinadas pelo Facebook|publisher=Destakjornal.com.br|accessdate=October 29, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824210926/http://www.destakjornal.com.br/readContent.aspx?id=10%2C101638|archivedate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> In one instance, 1,600 \"guests\" attended the 16th birthday party for a Hamburg girl who accidentally posted the invitation for the event as public. After reports of overcrowding, more than a hundred police were deployed for crowd control. A police officer was injured and eleven participants were arrested for assault, property damage and resistance to authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://librguides.com/facebook-blunder.html|title=Facebook blunder invites 15,000 to teen's 16th birthday party; 100 cops show up, too|publisher=LIBR Guides|date=July 18, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721185858/http://librguides.com/facebook-blunder.html|archivedate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> In another unexpectedly overcrowded event, 41 young people were arrested and at least 16 injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qualitytechtalk.com/best-comment-for-girl-pic-on-instagram/|title=Best comment on girl pic on Instagram|publisher=Sudarsan Chakraborty|language=English|accessdate=December 16, 2019|date=December 16, 2019}}|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}<br/>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/facebook-users-crash-public-birthday-party-in-hamburg/a-15131464|title=Facebook users crash 'public' birthday party in Hamburg|publisher=dw.com|language=English|accessdate=March 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319110911/http://www.dw.com/en/facebook-users-crash-public-birthday-party-in-hamburg/a-15131464|archive-date=March 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Facebook revealed Germany had blocked 84 posts from its citizens. These posts contained themes of Holocaust denial, which is illegal there.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2015, during the [[European migrant crisis]] with large numbers of immigrants entering the country unregulated, a broad discussion about the problems of mass immigration and politics of the actual government took place in social media. Early in 2016, a Bertelsmann company called \"[[Arvato services|Arvato]]\" was mandated to erase comments and contents from Facebook.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bertelsmann zensiert Facebook-Postings im Namen der Bundesregierung|url=http://www.neopresse.com/politik/dach/bertelsmann-facebook-hass-postings-fluechtlinge-bundesrergierung-zensur-loeschen/|website=NEOPresse \u2013 Unabh\u00e4ngige Nachrichten|accessdate=2016-01-21|language=de-DE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120222329/http://www.neopresse.com/politik/dach/bertelsmann-facebook-hass-postings-fluechtlinge-bundesrergierung-zensur-loeschen|archive-date=2016-01-20|url-status=live|date=2016-01-18}}</ref> In the summer of 2016, police in fourteen German states began coordinated raids on the residences of individuals who praised the Nazi regime or referred to refugees as \"scum\" in a private Facebook group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20160713/german-police-launch-first-nationwide-hate-speech-raids|title=German police launch first nationwide hate speech raids|accessdate=12 February 2018|date=13 July 2016|website=[[The Local]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213135117/https://www.thelocal.de/20160713/german-police-launch-first-nationwide-hate-speech-raids|archive-date=13 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A law known as NetzDG went into effect starting in 2018 which mandates all websites in Germany, including Facebook, censor such illegal content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/germany-implements-new-internet-hate-speech-crackdown/a-41991590|title=Germany implements new internet hate speech crackdown|date=1 January 2018|accessdate=12 February 2018|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210162046/http://www.dw.com/en/germany-implements-new-internet-hate-speech-crackdown/a-41991590|archive-date=10 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A spokesperson for Facebook announced the company's opposition to the law on the grounds that it would lead to overblocking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-41042266|title=Will Germany's new law kill free speech online?|first=Patrick|last=Evans|publisher=BBC|date=2017-09-18|accessdate=2018-06-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616210808/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-41042266|archive-date=2018-06-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===India===\n{{main|Internet censorship in India}}\nThe first time Facebook shared how often it allows governments to censor their citizens' content, they stated India had censored 4,765 posts in their country in the last six months of 2013. Facebook removed these posts in India under the government's claim of unlawful blasphemy of the state.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIndia posed three day ban on Facebook and other social sites during the riots in Punjab, Haryana and Chandigarh regarding Baba Ram Rahim Sing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/04/facebook-twitter-social-media-banned-kashmir-170426132038275.html|title=Facebook, Twitter, other social media banned in Kashmir|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=April 26, 2017|work=Al Jazeera|access-date=2017-09-10|location=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910023612/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/04/facebook-twitter-social-media-banned-kashmir-170426132038275.html|archive-date=September 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Censorship on Facebook increases 19% in 6 months in 2014; India leads the list of content removal.<ref>{{Cite book|title=India Digital Review|last=Business Insights|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe Indian government also imposed a six-month ban on Facebook, Twitter, and other social networking sites in Kashmir Valley in 2016-17, due to public safety because the Indian government believed social media were being misused by anti-national and anti-social elements backed by [[Pakistan Army]] and Pakistan intelligence agencies including [[Inter-Services Intelligence]]. The ban was also placed to cut communication between the terrorists, who were countering the efforts made by the [[Indian Army]].\n\n===Iran===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Iran}}\nAfter the [[Iran elections 2009|2009 election in Iran]], the website was banned because of fears that opposition movements were being organized on the website.<ref name=\"iran and iraq\"/>  However, after four years of the blocking of Facebook website, as of September 2013, the blocking of both Twitter and Facebook was thought to have been lifted without notice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mashable.com/2013/09/16/twitter-facebook-iran/|title=Iran Unblocks Twitter and Facebook|date=August 17, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013|agency=[[Mashable]]|work=Chris Taylor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829214714/http://mashable.com/2013/09/16/twitter-facebook-iran/|archive-date=August 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\nIranians lost unrestricted access to Facebook and Twitter the next day, leaving many people wondering whether the opening was deliberate or the result of some technical glitch.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/18/world/middleeast/facebook-and-twitter-blocked-again-in-iran-after-respite.html | work=The New York Times | first=Thomas | last=Erdbrink | title=Iran Bars Social Media Again After a Day | date=September 17, 2013 | access-date=February 21, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301180901/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/18/world/middleeast/facebook-and-twitter-blocked-again-in-iran-after-respite.html | archive-date=March 1, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\nIn September 2016, the [[Israeli government|Cabinet of Israel]] has said to have agreed with Facebook to remove content that is deemed as incitement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/sep/12/facebook-israel-monitor-posts-incite-violence-social-media?CMP=twt_gu|title=Facebook and Israel to work to monitor posts that incite violence|date=2016-12-09|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=2018-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104073223/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/sep/12/facebook-israel-monitor-posts-incite-violence-social-media?CMP=twt_gu|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/12/30/facebook-says-it-is-deleting-accounts-at-the-direction-of-the-u-s-and-israeli-governments/|title=Facebook Says It Is Deleting Accounts at the Direction of the U.S. and Israeli Governments|date=2016-12-09|website=The Intercept|access-date=2018-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103225231/https://theintercept.com/2017/12/30/facebook-says-it-is-deleting-accounts-at-the-direction-of-the-u-s-and-israeli-governments/|archive-date=2018-01-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/09/12/facebook-is-collaborating-with-the-israeli-government-to-determine-what-should-be-censored/|title=Facebook is collaborating with the Israeli government to determine what should be censored|date=2017-12-30|website=The Intercept|access-date=2018-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104192338/https://theintercept.com/2016/09/12/facebook-is-collaborating-with-the-israeli-government-to-determine-what-should-be-censored/|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> Israel has one of the most openly cooperative relationships with Facebook and the Israeli Justice Ministery boasted that Facebook had removed 95 percent of its requested content.<ref name=\"Taibbi\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/who-will-fix-facebook-759916/|title=Who Will Fix Facebook?|last=Taibbi|first=Matt|last2=Taibbi|first2=Matt|date=2018-11-26|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070635/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/who-will-fix-facebook-759916/|archive-date=2019-05-10|url-status=live}}</ref> This announcement came after top Facebook officials met with the Israeli government to determine which Facebook accounts should be deleted on the grounds that they constituted as incitement. The [[Israel]]i interior minister's office has said that they agreed with Facebook representatives to create teams that would figure out how best to monitor and remove \"inflammatory content\" online.\n\nAhead of municipal elections in 2018, Israel\u2019s National Cyber Directorate has stated that Facebook was banning \"thousands\" of accounts ahead of the elections. Critics of Israel\u2019s policies are not happy with this move as they claim this is being used as a way to silence outspoken [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] civilians, activists and journalists. The activists argue that when they post material meant to critique [[Palestinian territories|the occupation]], Israel sees it as encouraging violence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/palestinian-activists-facebook_us_57ed66bce4b082aad9ba1122|title=Palestinian Activists Are Angry About Alleged Facebook Censorship|date=2016-09-29|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115141659/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/palestinian-activists-facebook_us_57ed66bce4b082aad9ba1122|archive-date=2018-01-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Some believe that the Israeli government and Facebook have an \"informal arrangement\" for monitoring Facebook content. Jordana Cutler, who previously was the [[Chief of staff|Chief of Staff]] at the [[Embassy of Israel in Washington, D.C.|Israel Embassy in Washington DC]] and a former adviser to Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] is Facebook\u2019s head of policy in Israel. She claimed that Facebook is merely following suggestions. \u201cWe receive requests from the government but are not committed to them,\u201d Cutler said.<ref name=\"Taibbi\"/>\n\n===North Korea===\n{{main|Internet in North Korea}}\nIn April 2016, North Korea started blocking Facebook, \"a move underscoring its concern with the spread of online information,\" according to [[The Associated Press]]. Anyone who tries to access it without special permission from the North Korean government, will be subject to punishment.<ref name=NK>{{Cite web| title = North Korea blocks Facebook, Twitter and YouTube| work = [[The Associated Press]]| date = 4 April 2016| accessdate = 4 April 2016| url = http://globalnews.ca/news/2616449/north-korea-blacks-facebook-twitter-and-youtube/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160406095746/http://globalnews.ca/news/2616449/north-korea-blacks-facebook-twitter-and-youtube/| archive-date = 6 April 2016| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n===Malaysia===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Malaysia}}\nFacebook was blocked for a few days in [[Malaysia]] during the [[2011 Egyptian protests]].<ref name=\"inaccessible in Egypt\"/>\n\n===Mauritius===\nThe Information and Communication Technologies Authority (ICTA) of [[Mauritius]], ordered [[Internet Service Provider|internet service providers]] of the country to ban [[Facebook]] on immediate effect, on the 8 November 2007 because of a fake profile page of the Prime Minister. Access to Facebook was restored on the next day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.noulakaz.net/weblog/2007/11/08/facebook-a-mauritian-tragedy/ |title=Facebook: A Mauritian tragedy? |publisher=Noulakaz |date=2007-11-08 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723230916/http://www.noulakaz.net/weblog/2007/11/08/facebook-a-mauritian-tragedy/ |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pascalg.wordpress.com/2007/11/08/facebook-outage-in-mauritius-its-been-censored/ |title=Facebook outage in Mauritius \u2013 it's been censored!!! &#124; Sometimes life is good... |publisher=Pascalg.wordpress.com |date=2007-11-08 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824024531/http://pascalg.wordpress.com/2007/11/08/facebook-outage-in-mauritius-its-been-censored/ |archive-date=2011-08-24 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexpress.mu/services/archive-97239-maurice-censure-le-site-communautaire-facebook.html|title=Maurice censure le site communautaire Facebook|publisher=L'express|accessdate=9 Nov 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120913202342/http://www.lexpress.mu/services/archive-97239-maurice-censure-le-site-communautaire-facebook.html|archivedate=2012-09-13}}</ref>\n\n===Morocco===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Morocco}}\nOn February 5, 2008, [[Fouad Mourtada]], a citizen of Morocco, was arrested for 43 days due to the alleged creation of a faked Facebook profile of [[Prince Moulay Rachid of Morocco]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/02/07/morocco.facebook/index.html?eref=rss_latest|title=Police arrest man for 'villainous' theft of prince's ID on Facebook|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 5, 2008|date=February 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215102125/http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/02/07/morocco.facebook/index.html?eref=rss_latest|archive-date=February 15, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/07/world/africa/07briefs-identity.html?ex=1360040400&en=28cce9bbc525d4cd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|title=Moroccan held for alleged royal ID theft|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 5, 2008|date=February 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215102635/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/07/world/africa/07briefs-identity.html?ex=1360040400&en=28cce9bbc525d4cd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|archive-date=February 15, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\nOn May 19, 2010, [[Lahore High Court]] ordered Facebook to be blocked. Facebook was blocked until May 31 after a competition page encouraged users to post drawings of The Holy Prophet Hazrat Mohammad SAW. The controversial page named \u201cDraw Mohammad SAW Day\u201d had been created by a Facebook user in response to American cartoonist Molly Noris\u2019s protest to the decision of US television channel, Comedy Central to cancel an episode of the popular show \u201cSouth Park\u201d over its depiction of Mohammed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/pakistan/7740295/Facebook-blocked-in-Pakistan-over-Prophet-Mohammed-cartoon-row.html|title=Facebook blocked in Pakistan over Prophet Mohammed cartoon row|last=Crilly|first=Rob|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=19 May 2010|work=|access-date=31 May 2019|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100520031525/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/pakistan/7740295/Facebook-blocked-in-Pakistan-over-Prophet-Mohammed-cartoon-row.html|archive-date=20 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Noris had however disavowed having declared May 20 \u201cDraw Muhammad Day\u201d and had condemned the effort and issued an apology. The ban, implemented by the [[Pakistan Telecommunication Authority]], also resulted in a ban on YouTube and restricted access to other websites, including Wikipedia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/may/31/pakistan-lifts-facebook-ban|title=Pakistan lifts Facebook ban but 'blasphemous' pages stay hidden|last=Walsh|first=Declan|date=31 May 2010|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 May 2019|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531090225/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/may/31/pakistan-lifts-facebook-ban|archive-date=31 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 2017, the [[NetBlocks]] internet shutdown observatory and [[Digital Rights Foundation]] collected evidence of nationwide blocking of Facebook alongside other social media services, imposed by the government in response to the violent [[2017 Tehreek-e-Labaik protest|Tehreek-e-Labaik protests]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://digitalrightsfoundation.pk/press-release-drf-and-netblocks-find-blanket-and-nation-wide-ban-on-social-media-in-pakistan-and-demand-it-to-be-lifted-immediately/|title=DRF and NetBlocks find blanket and nation-wide ban on social media in Pakistan and demand it to be lifted immediately|date=2017-11-26|work=Digital Rights Foundation|access-date=2017-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040815/https://digitalrightsfoundation.pk/press-release-drf-and-netblocks-find-blanket-and-nation-wide-ban-on-social-media-in-pakistan-and-demand-it-to-be-lifted-immediately/|archive-date=2017-12-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nation.com.pk/27-Nov-2017/activists-assail-blanket-ban-on-social-media|title=Activists assail blanket ban on social media|date=2017-11-27|work=The Nation|access-date=2017-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128200108/http://nation.com.pk/27-Nov-2017/activists-assail-blanket-ban-on-social-media|archive-date=2017-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/social-buzz/2017/11/need-know-nation-wide-internet-disruptions-dharna/|title=All you need to know about nation-wide internet disruptions during dharna|date=2017-11-27|website=Samaa TV|access-date=2017-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127185835/https://www.samaa.tv/social-buzz/2017/11/need-know-nation-wide-internet-disruptions-dharna/|archive-date=2017-11-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The technical investigation found that all major Pakistani fixed-line and mobile service providers were affected by the restrictions, which were lifted by the PTA the next day when protests abated following the resignation of [[Minister for Law and Justice (Pakistan)|Minister for Law and Justice]] [[Zahid Hamid]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nation.com.pk/26-Nov-2017/the-issue-of-social-media-networking|title=The issue of social media networking|date=2017-11-26|work=The Nation|access-date=2017-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128200126/http://nation.com.pk/26-Nov-2017/the-issue-of-social-media-networking|archive-date=2017-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Other websites including Twitter, YouTube and Dailymotion were also reportedly blocked by order of the PTA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ifex.org/pakistan/2017/11/28/tv-news-suspended/|title=Pakistan suspends TV news channels and social media sites to block protest coverage|publisher=ifex|date=29 November 2017|access-date=29 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129095415/https://ifex.org/pakistan/2017/11/28/tv-news-suspended/|archive-date=29 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\nIn 2014, Russia demanded that all links on Facebook be blocked that supported Russian opposition Aleksei A. Navalny. Facebook users were blocked from any protest supporting Aleksei.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Facebook should Stop Cooperating with Russian Government Censorship.|last=Somin|first=llya|publisher=Washington: WP Company LLC d/b/a The Washington Post|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> This included about ten million Facebook users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/02/business/international/web-freedom-is-seen-to-be-growing-as-a-global-issue-in-2015.html|title=Web Freedom Is Seen as a Growing Global Issue|last=Goel|first=Vindu|date=2015-01-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-10|last2=Kramer|first2=Andrew E.|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070628/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/02/business/international/web-freedom-is-seen-to-be-growing-as-a-global-issue-in-2015.html|archive-date=2019-05-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Sri Lanka===\n{{main|Censorship in Sri Lanka}}\nIn March 2018, Facebook was blocked for 3 days in [[Sri Lanka]] due to racial hate speeches being rumored around the country via the social media which caused many riots in the country by extremist groups. However this decision was not permanent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Tense-situ-in-Teldeniya-over-death-of-assault-victim-146768.html|title=Tense situ in Teldeniya over death of assault victim|publisher=|access-date=2018-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315003725/http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Tense-situ-in-Teldeniya-over-death-of-assault-victim-146768.html|archive-date=2018-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"guard\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/14/facebook-accused-by-sri-lanka-of-failing-to-control-hate-speech |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=Sri Lanka accuses Facebook over hate speech after deadly riots |first=Michael |last=Safi |date=March 14, 2018 |quote=As mobs of hardline Buddhists rioted and lit fires in towns in the central district of Kandy, Facebook, WhatsApp and several other platforms were blocked across the country [...] Both Facebook and WhatsApp remain restricted but the Guardian understands the block on the latter could be lifted by Wednesday evening.}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2019, Facebook was blocked along with other social media sites until April 30, 2019 in [[Sri Lanka]] to prevent the false information about [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings|Easter Sunday bombings]] spreading around the country via the social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/04/21/sri-lanka-bans-social-media-after-bombings|title=Sri Lanka temporarily bans social media after terrorist bombings|website=engadget.com|date=April 21, 2019|access-date=April 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502222749/https://www.engadget.com/2019/04/21/sri-lanka-bans-social-media-after-bombings/|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/30/social-media-ban-lifted|title=Social media ban lifted|publisher=Newsfirst.lk|date=April 30, 2019|access-date=April 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430053155/https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/30/social-media-ban-lifted/|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2019, the [[Sri Lanka]]n government has reimposed a ban on social media platforms in an effort to stop the spread of rumours after violence erupted between groups of civilians in Negombo, north of the capital and site of one of the [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings|Easter Sunday bombings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sri-lanka-blasts-curfew/sri-lanka-imposes-curfew-in-negombo-after-clashes-bans-social-media-idUSL3N22H0EF|title=Sri Lanka imposes curfew in Negombo after clashes, bans social media|publisher=Reuters.com|date=May 5, 2019|access-date=May 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505193610/https://www.reuters.com/article/sri-lanka-blasts-curfew/sri-lanka-imposes-curfew-in-negombo-after-clashes-bans-social-media-idUSL3N22H0EF|archive-date=May 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban was lifted on May 6, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/May06_1557116757CH.php|title=Temporary ban on social media platforms lifted|publisher=Colombopage.com|date=May 6, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513034310/http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/May06_1557116757CH.php|archive-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2019, the [[Sri Lanka]]n government temporarily banned social media including Facebook. This measure has been taken owing to the false propaganda carried out by the social media and the unrest which had occurred in several areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/55087/social-media-temporarily-banned|title=Social media temporarily banned|publisher=AdaDerana.lk|date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513034950/http://www.adaderana.lk/news/55087/social-media-temporarily-banned|archive-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban was lifted on May 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adaderana.lk/news/55200/social-media-ban-in-sri-lanka-lifted|title=Social media ban in Sri Lanka lifted|publisher=AdaDerana.lk|date=May 17, 2019|access-date=May 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518205447/https://www.adaderana.lk/news/55200/social-media-ban-in-sri-lanka-lifted|archive-date=May 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Sudan===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Sudan}}\nIn December 2018, the [[Sudan]]ese government blocked Facebook, along with other [[social media]] sites, which were being used by anti-government protesters to organize [[Sudanese protests (2018\u201319)|protests against President Omar al-Bashir]].<ref name=\"netblocks.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/social-media-access-restored-across-sudan-noy9dnB3|title=Social media access restored across Sudan|date=2019-02-26|website=[[NetBlocks]]|access-date=2019-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043048/https://netblocks.org/reports/social-media-access-restored-across-sudan-noy9dnB3|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sudan-protests-internet-idUSKCN1OW0Z7|title=Sudan restricts social media access to counter protest movement|date=2019-01-02|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306111406/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sudan-protests-internet-idUSKCN1OW0Z7|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://qz.com/africa/1510229/sudan-shuts-down-facebook-twitter-instagram-amid-bread-protests/ |title=Sudan has blocked Facebook, Twitter and Instagram to counter anti-govt protests |access-date=2018-12-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228235548/https://qz.com/africa/1510229/sudan-shuts-down-facebook-twitter-instagram-amid-bread-protests/ |archive-date=2018-12-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> The restrictions were lifted 68 days later following the introduction of emergency measures outlawing public demonstrations.<ref name=\"netblocks.org\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-sudan-protests-emergency-idUKKCN1QE26I|title=Sudan's Bashir bans protests in new emergency measures|date=2019-02-25|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043806/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-sudan-protests-emergency-idUKKCN1QE26I|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Syria===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Syria}}\nThe Syrian government explained their ban by claiming the website promoted attacks on authorities.<ref name=\"syria\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSOWE37285020071123|title=Syria blocks Facebook in Internet crackdown|accessdate=March 5, 2008|author=Yacoub Oweis, Khaled|work=Reuters|date=November 23, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201114242/http://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSOWE37285020071123|archive-date=February 1, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Syrian-govt-blocks-use-of-Facebook| title=Syrian gov't blocks use of Facebook| work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]| date=November 24, 2007| accessdate=March 8, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301180845/http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Syrian-govt-blocks-use-of-Facebook| archive-date=March 1, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> The government also feared [[Mossad|Israeli]] infiltration of Syrian social networks on Facebook.<ref name=\"syria\" /> Facebook was also used by Syrian citizens to criticize the [[government of Syria]], as public criticism of the Syrian government used to be punishable by imprisonment.<ref name=\"syria\" /> In February 2011, Facebook was un-blocked from all ISP's and the website remains to be accessible.<ref>{{Citation\n| url = https://www.dawn.com/news/1320650\n| title = Tajikistan blocks Facebook access to silence critics\n| publisher = [[Reuters]]\n| location = International\n| date = November 27, 2012\n| access-date = November 7, 2017\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171107221944/https://www.dawn.com/news/1320650\n| archive-date = November 7, 2017\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n===Tajikistan===\nIn November 2012, [[Tajikistan]] blocked access to Facebook in response to comments posted online, spreading \u201cmud and slander\u201d about President [[Emomalii Rahmon]] and various other officials.<ref>{{Citation\n| url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/27/net-us-tajikistan-facebook-idUSBRE8AQ0JY20121127\n| title = Could it happen again? Remembering Pakistan's Facebook, YouTube ban\n| publisher = [[Dawn Media Group|Dawn]]\n| location = International\n| date = March 27, 2017\n| access-date = June 30, 2017\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172245/http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/27/net-us-tajikistan-facebook-idUSBRE8AQ0JY20121127\n| archive-date = September 24, 2015\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Thailand}}\nIn 2017, Thailand asked Facebook to remove 309 posted items that were said to be illegal by standards of Thailand. However, Facebook only deleted 178 of the items, leaving 131 still on Facebook. Thai authorities stated if they found any illegal content in the remaining 131 posts they would ban all 14.8 million users from Facebook, instead of taking legal action. All posts ended up being removed from Facebook, preventing the shutdown of Facebook in Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.ezp.mesacc.edu/login?qurl=http://link.galegroup.com%2fapps%2fdoc%2fA493945757%2fITOF%3fu%3dmcc_mesa%26sid%3dITOF%26xid%3d341adb3a|title=Off-Campus eResource Access - Paul A. Elsner Library @ Mesa Community College|website=login.ezp.mesacc.edu|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Tunisia ===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Tunisia}}\nFacebook was a major part of the political uprisings of the \u2018Arab Spring\u2019 in 2011.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aal|first=Konstantin|last2=Schorch|first2=Mar\u00e9n|last3=Elkilani|first3=Esma Ben Hadj|last4=Wulf|first4=Volker|date=2019-05-28|title=Facebook and the Mass Media in Tunisia|url=https://www001.zimt.uni-siegen.de/ojs/index.php/mia/article/view/36|journal=Media in Action|language=en|issue=1|pages=135\u2013168}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkey ===\n{{main|Internet regulation in Turkey}}\nAfter photos of Mehmet Selim Kiraz being held at gun point by two terrorists began circulation on social media on April 6, 2015, the Turkish government banned Facebook, Twitter, Youtube, and 166 other websites in the country for hours. The government does not tolerate \"anti-government propaganda,\" and their laws are becoming increasingly more strict. In the 2015 Press Freedom Index from Reporters Without Borders, Turkey ranked 149 of 180 countries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2015/0406/Turkey-turns-off-Twitter-and-Facebook-as-censorship-grows|title=Turkey turns off Twitter and Facebook as censorship grows|date=2015-04-06|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2019-05-10|issn=0882-7729|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510072126/https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2015/0406/Turkey-turns-off-Twitter-and-Facebook-as-censorship-grows|archive-date=2019-05-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\nFacebook was blocked at 11.30pm on Feb 27 2020, along with several other social media sites. It happened the day that the military crisis in Idlib escalated.<ref>https://netblocks.org/reports/social-media-blocked-in-turkey-as-idlib-military-crisis-escalates-r8VWGXA5</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{main|Internet censorship in the United Kingdom}}\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] on April 28, 2011, the day before the [[wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton]], a number of politically motivated Facebook groups and pages were removed or suspended from the website as part of a nationwide crackdown on political activity. The groups and pages were mostly concerned with opposition to government spending cuts, and many were used to organize demonstrations in a continuation of the [[2010 UK student protests]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/29/facebook-activist-pages-purged | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Shiv | last=Malik | title=Activists claim purge of Facebook pages | date=April 29, 2011 | access-date=December 17, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019200501/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/29/facebook-activist-pages-purged | archive-date=October 19, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Chan4News-29April2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/facebook-suspends-uk-activist-groups |title=Facebook 'suspends UK activist groups' - Channel 4 News |publisher=Channel4.com |date=2011-04-29 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903124202/http://www.channel4.com/news/facebook-suspends-uk-activist-groups |archive-date=2011-09-03 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-29April2011\">{{cite news | url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/29/facebook-deactivates-protest-pages-in-britain/ | work=The New York Times | first=Jennifer | last=Preston | title=Facebook Deactivates Protest Pages in Britain | date=April 29, 2011 | access-date=May 14, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503215815/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/29/facebook-deactivates-protest-pages-in-britain/ | archive-date=May 3, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref> The censorship of the pages coincided with a series of pre-emptive arrests of known activists.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/29/royal-wedding-police-criticised-protesters | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Robert | last1=Booth | first2=Sandra | last2=Laville | first3=Shiv | last3=Malik | title=Royal wedding: police criticised for pre-emptive strikes against protesters | date=April 29, 2011 | access-date=December 17, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005100702/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/29/royal-wedding-police-criticised-protesters | archive-date=October 5, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> Amongst the arrestees were a communist and socialist, and a few members of a street theater group planning an [[effigy]] beheading performance in opposition to the monarchy.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-13234682 | work=BBC News | title=Royal wedding: Three held over effigy beheading claims | date=April 29, 2011 | access-date=July 21, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221135142/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-13234682 | archive-date=December 21, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA Facebook spokesman said the pages were disabled as part of a routine sweep because they were created with fake personal profiles, a violation of the company\u2019s term of service. In this case a number of the Facebook personal profile pages represented causes, rather than real people. Facebook \"offered to help convert the profiles to pages that are designed to represent companies, groups or causes.\"<ref name=\"NYT-29April2011\"/> The spokesman went on to say that \"the Met Police did not ask Facebook to take down this content.\"<ref name=\"Chan4News-29April2011\"/>\n\nIn March 2018, far-right [[Britain First]] was removed by Facebook. The pages of the leaders of the party were also taken down following their arrest and incarceration.\n\n===Vietnam===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Vietnam}}\nFacebook was blocked in Vietnam for two weeks in May 2016 due to [[protest]] of dissidents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/17/facebook-blocked-in-vietnam-over-the-weekend-due-to-citizen-protests/|title=Facebook blocked in Vietnam over the weekend due to citizen protest|work=TechCrunch|accessdate=May 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206073825/https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/17/facebook-blocked-in-vietnam-over-the-weekend-due-to-citizen-protests/|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVietnam Facebook users total about 52 million and is a vital tool for their day to day use. However, the government is not accountable to the people which causes abuse of censorship in Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite book|title=How Facebook is damaging freedom of expression in Vietnam|last=Khoi|first=M|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In 2018, the government created a huge military unit to block posts containing \"wrong views\" online. To appease the government, Facebook removed 160 \"toxic\" accounts for speech against the Communist Party in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/theworldpost/wp/2018/02/19/vietnam-internet/|title=Vietnam's Internet is in trouble|last=Luong|first=Dien|date=February 19, 2018|website=The Washington Post|access-date=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070651/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/theworldpost/wp/2018/02/19/vietnam-internet/|archive-date=May 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Criticism of Facebook#Censorship controversies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist| 30em}}\n\n{{Censorship and websites}}\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{Internet censorship circumvention technologies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Censorship of Facebook}}\n[[Category:Internet censorship by organization|Facebook]]\n[[Category:Facebook]]\n[[Category:Facebook criticisms and controversies]]\n[[Category:Internet censorship in China]]\n[[Category:Censorship]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Internet censorship}}\n[[File:Facebook Logo (2019).svg|right|266px|[[Facebook]] logo]]Facebook has been replacing traditional media channels since its founding in 2003.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bozdag|first=Engin|date=2013-09-01|title=Bias in algorithmic filtering and personalization|journal=Ethics and Information Technology|language=en|volume=15|issue=3|pages=209\u2013227|doi=10.1007/s10676-013-9321-6|issn=1572-8439}}</ref> Censorship in the media, especially on Facebook is because of a variety of reasons, since Facebook accepts all kinds of content, with little or no moderation, and displays what people post publicly, this practice can sometimes threaten oppressive governments especially in totalitarian regimes while also propelling fake news, hate speech and misinformation thus undermining the credibility of online platforms and social media. Many countries have banned or temporarily limited access to the [[social networking website]] [[Facebook]], including [[Mainland China]],<ref name=\"chinablock\">{{cite web\n |title=China's Facebook Status: Blocked\n |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/theworldnewser/2009/07/chinas-facebook-status-blocked.html\n |date=July 8, 2009\n |publisher=ABC News9\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090711081856/http://blogs.abcnews.com/theworldnewser/2009/07/chinas-facebook-status-blocked.html\n |archivedate=2009-07-11\n }}</ref> [[Iran]],<ref name=\"iran and iraq\">{{cite web|accessdate=April 30, 2008|url=http://www.hamsaweb.org/crime/4.html|title=Facebook Faces Censorship in Iran|publisher=[[American Islamic Congress]]|date=August 29, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424001859/http://www.hamsaweb.org/crime/4.html#|archive-date=2008-04-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Syria]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-facebook-idUSOWE37285020071123|title=Syria blocks Facebook in Internet crackdown|date=2007-11-23|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-12-16|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201164617/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-facebook-idUSOWE37285020071123|archive-date=2019-12-01|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[North Korea]].<ref name=NK/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/this-is-how-kashmiris-are-using-facebook-twitter-despite-modi-govt-ban-on-social-media/357618/|title=This is how Kashmiris are using Facebook, Twitter despite Modi govt ban on social media|last=Javaid|first=Azaan|date=2020-02-01|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> Use of the website has also been restricted in various ways in other countries. As of May 2016, the only countries to ban access around the clock to the social networking site are China, Iran, Syria, and North Korea. However, since most North Korean residents have no access to the Internet,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/tech/north-koreas-internet-is-as-weird-as-you-think-it-is|title=North Korea's internet is as weird as you think it is|date=9 November 2017|access-date=31 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531090225/https://www.foxnews.com/tech/north-koreas-internet-is-as-weird-as-you-think-it-is|archive-date=31 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> China and Iran are the only countries where access to Facebook is actively restricted in a wholesale manner.\n\n== Algorithmic Censorship ==\nOnline censorship by Facebook of algorithmic forms raises concerns including the surveillance of all instant communications and the use of machine learning systems with the [[Algorithmic bias|potential for errors and biases]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cobbe|first=Jennifer|date=2019-08-14|title=Algorithmic Censorship on Social Platforms: Power, Legitimacy, and Resistance|language=en|location=Rochester, NY|ssrn=3437304}}</ref> Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook\u2019s CEO and majority shareholder, published a memo on censorship. \u201cWhat should be the limits to what people can express?\u201d he asked. \u201cWhat content should be distributed and what should be blocked? Who should decide these policies and make enforcement decisions?\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2018/12/facebook-punish-censorship/577654/|title=The Speech That Facebook Plans to Punish|last=Friedersdorf|first=Conor|date=2018-12-11|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115132324/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2018/12/facebook-punish-censorship/577654/|archive-date=2019-11-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Facebook has been giving permission for instant removals of content and censoring what the public can see. An example of this is journalist [[Ford Fischer]] immediately being banned from posting content for 3 days as he \ntried to share an article about his censorship on YouTube.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reclaimthenet.org/facebook-bans-ford-fischer-links/|title=Facebook bans journalist Ford Fischer from posting links as he attempted to share YouTube censorship article|date=2019-12-17|website=Reclaim The Net|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship by country==\n\n=== Austria ===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Austria}}\nLike France and Germany, Austria has laws prohibiting [[Holocaust denial]]. This caused 78 Facebook posts to be banned from the country in 2013.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://web-a-ebscohost-com.ezp.mesacc.edu/ehost/detail/detail?vid=43&sid=478b8a6a-822d-4e40-919b-f968207ac5cb%40sdc-v-sessmgr06&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d#AN=95955653&db=aph|title=Facebook Reveals Which Countries Censor Your Newsfeed|last=Stamper|first=Laura|date=2014-04-15|website=Time|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh===\n{{see also|Blasphemy law in Bangladesh}}\nBangladesh (like Iran, China and North Korea) had banned Facebook before - the Bangladeshi ban operated for a short period of time {{when|date=April 2017}}. The [[Awami League]]-led [[government of Bangladesh]] announced a countrywide ban on Facebook and other social-network websites. Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]] (in office from 2009) proposed the establishment of an [[Internet surveillance|Internet monitoring]] committee with the help of Bangladesh's intelligence services. Right-wing political parties and groups in Bangladesh protested against bloggers and others they had considered \"blasphemous\" at the time of the proposal. Extremists in the country had [[Attacks on secularists in Bangladesh|murdered eight secularists]], including atheist blogger [[Ahmed Rajib Haider]], who was fatally stabbed in February 2013. National riots over the country's war-crimes trials resulted in the deaths of 56 people between 19 January 2013 and 2 March 2013.\n\nOn 18 November 2015 the same Awami League government banned Facebook again on the eve of the final judgement of [[Bangladesh Jamaat-e-Islami]] leader Ali Ahsan Muhammad Mujahid and [[Bangladesh Nationalist Party]] leader Salauddin Kader Chowdhury. Both the politicians and previous minister have been issued a death sentence by the War Criminals Tribunal and the review board of the Supreme Court of Bangladesh has finally given their judgement in favour of the previously given one.\n\nThe Bangladesh government lifted the ban on 20 December 2015. Facebook is accessible in Bangladesh as of late 2017.\n\n===China===\n{{main|Internet censorship in China}}\n\n[[Internet censorship in the People's Republic of China|In China]], Facebook was blocked following the [[July 2009 \u00dcr\u00fcmqi riots]]  because [[East Turkestan independence movement|Xinjiang independence activists]] were using Facebook as part of their communications network, and Facebook denied giving the information of the terrorists.<ref>{{cite web|title= 80 pct of netizens agree China should punish Facebook|url= http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90776/90882/6697993.html|date= July 10, 2009|publisher= The [[People's Daily Online]]|accessdate= July 13, 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090714121501/http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90776/90882/6697993.html|archive-date= July 14, 2009|url-status= live}}</ref> Some Chinese users also believed that Facebook would not succeed in China after [[Google China]]'s [[Operation Aurora|problems]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Facebook\u4e0a\u6f14\u620f\u5267 \u7eb8\u8001\u864e\"\u975e\u6b7b\u4e0d\u53ef\"|url= http://blog.sina.com.cn/s/blog_000ed7d80100i79k.html|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131214040727/http://blog.sina.com.cn/s/blog_000ed7d80100i79k.html|archive-date= December 14, 2013|url-status= dead|access-date= December 10, 2013}}</ref> [[Renren]] (formerly ''Xiaonei'') has many features similar to Facebook, and complies with PRC Government regulations regarding content filtering.\n\nAs of 20 August 2013, there have been reports of Facebook being partially unblocked in China.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.headlineasia.com/facebook-and-twitter-in-china/ |title=Facebook And Twitter In China! |date=2013-08-20 |accessdate=2013-12-10 |website=Headline Asia |publisher=[[South China Morning Post]] |publication-date=2013-08-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212145054/http://www.headlineasia.com/facebook-and-twitter-in-china/ |archivedate=2013-12-12 }}</ref> However, according to the \"Blocked in China\" website, Facebook is still blocked as of December 7, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blockedinchina.net/?siteurl=facebook.com |title=Test If Any Website Is Blocked In China |website=BlockedInChina.net |accessdate=August 2, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129121311/http://www.blockedinchina.net/?siteurl=facebook.com |archive-date=January 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is not blocked in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]]. Facebook is currently working on a censorship project for China, where a third party would be allowed to regulate on Facebook and control popular stories that come around. This would be a huge attempt on Facebook to get back into China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.ezp.mesacc.edu/login?qurl=http://link.galegroup.com%2fapps%2fdoc%2fA474768520%2fITBC%3fu%3dmcc_mesa%26sid%3dITBC%26xid%3d9a60479f|title=Off-Campus eResource Access - Paul A. Elsner Library @ Mesa Community College|website=login.ezp.mesacc.edu|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n===Egypt===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Egypt}}\nblocked for a few days in [[Egypt]] during the [[2011 Egyptian protests]].<ref name=\"inaccessible in Egypt\">{{cite news\n| url=  https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jK3UhbzReiwvzyJImym-FEeZb87A?docId=CNG.737c6f9342ecee94153df06ff00b5617.a1\n| title=  Facebook reported inaccessible in Egypt\n| publisher=  [[Google]]/[[Agence France-Presse]]\n| date=  26 Jan 2011\n| accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\nLike Austria and Germany, France has laws prohibiting [[Holocaust denial]]. Because of this, a reported 80 Facebook posts were blocked from the French people in 2013.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Germany===\nIn July 2011, authorities in Germany began to discuss the prohibition of events organized on Facebook. The decision is based on numerous cases of overcrowding by people who were not originally invited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ptjornal.com/201107041737/mundo/alemanha-festas-convocadas-pelo-facebook-sao-ameaca-a-ordem-publica.html |title=Alemanha: Festas convocadas pelo Facebook s\u00e3o \"amea\u00e7a \u00e0 ordem p\u00fablica\"|publisher=Ptjornal.com|accessdate=October 29, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904145814/http://www.ptjornal.com/201107041737/mundo/alemanha-festas-convocadas-pelo-facebook-sao-ameaca-a-ordem-publica.html|archivedate=September 4, 2011}}<br/>{{cite web|url=http://www.destakjornal.com.br/readContent.aspx?id=10,101638|title=Alemanha pode proibir festas combinadas pelo Facebook|publisher=Destakjornal.com.br|accessdate=October 29, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824210926/http://www.destakjornal.com.br/readContent.aspx?id=10%2C101638|archivedate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> In one instance, 1,600 \"guests\" attended the 16th birthday party for a Hamburg girl who accidentally posted the invitation for the event as public. After reports of overcrowding, more than a hundred police were deployed for crowd control. A police officer was injured and eleven participants were arrested for assault, property damage and resistance to authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://librguides.com/facebook-blunder.html|title=Facebook blunder invites 15,000 to teen's 16th birthday party; 100 cops show up, too|publisher=LIBR Guides|date=July 18, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721185858/http://librguides.com/facebook-blunder.html|archivedate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> In another unexpectedly overcrowded event, 41 young people were arrested and at least 16 injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qualitytechtalk.com/best-comment-for-girl-pic-on-instagram/|title=Best comment on girl pic on Instagram|publisher=Sudarsan Chakraborty|language=English|accessdate=December 16, 2019|date=December 16, 2019}}|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}<br/>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/facebook-users-crash-public-birthday-party-in-hamburg/a-15131464|title=Facebook users crash 'public' birthday party in Hamburg|publisher=dw.com|language=English|accessdate=March 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319110911/http://www.dw.com/en/facebook-users-crash-public-birthday-party-in-hamburg/a-15131464|archive-date=March 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Facebook revealed Germany had blocked 84 posts from its citizens. These posts contained themes of Holocaust denial, which is illegal there.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2015, during the [[European migrant crisis]] with large numbers of immigrants entering the country unregulated, a broad discussion about the problems of mass immigration and politics of the actual government took place in social media. Early in 2016, a Bertelsmann company called \"[[Arvato services|Arvato]]\" was mandated to erase comments and contents from Facebook.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bertelsmann zensiert Facebook-Postings im Namen der Bundesregierung|url=http://www.neopresse.com/politik/dach/bertelsmann-facebook-hass-postings-fluechtlinge-bundesrergierung-zensur-loeschen/|website=NEOPresse \u2013 Unabh\u00e4ngige Nachrichten|accessdate=2016-01-21|language=de-DE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120222329/http://www.neopresse.com/politik/dach/bertelsmann-facebook-hass-postings-fluechtlinge-bundesrergierung-zensur-loeschen|archive-date=2016-01-20|url-status=live|date=2016-01-18}}</ref> In the summer of 2016, police in fourteen German states began coordinated raids on the residences of individuals who praised the Nazi regime or referred to refugees as \"scum\" in a private Facebook group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20160713/german-police-launch-first-nationwide-hate-speech-raids|title=German police launch first nationwide hate speech raids|accessdate=12 February 2018|date=13 July 2016|website=[[The Local]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213135117/https://www.thelocal.de/20160713/german-police-launch-first-nationwide-hate-speech-raids|archive-date=13 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A law known as NetzDG went into effect starting in 2018 which mandates all websites in Germany, including Facebook, censor such illegal content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/germany-implements-new-internet-hate-speech-crackdown/a-41991590|title=Germany implements new internet hate speech crackdown|date=1 January 2018|accessdate=12 February 2018|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210162046/http://www.dw.com/en/germany-implements-new-internet-hate-speech-crackdown/a-41991590|archive-date=10 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A spokesperson for Facebook announced the company's opposition to the law on the grounds that it would lead to overblocking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-41042266|title=Will Germany's new law kill free speech online?|first=Patrick|last=Evans|publisher=BBC|date=2017-09-18|accessdate=2018-06-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616210808/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-41042266|archive-date=2018-06-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===India===\n{{main|Internet censorship in India}}\nThe first time Facebook shared how often it allows governments to censor their citizens' content, they stated India had censored 4,765 posts in their country in the last six months of 2013. Facebook removed these posts in India under the government's claim of unlawful blasphemy of the state.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIndia posed three day ban on Facebook and other social sites during the riots in Punjab, Haryana and Chandigarh regarding Baba Ram Rahim Sing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/04/facebook-twitter-social-media-banned-kashmir-170426132038275.html|title=Facebook, Twitter, other social media banned in Kashmir|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=April 26, 2017|work=Al Jazeera|access-date=2017-09-10|location=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910023612/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/04/facebook-twitter-social-media-banned-kashmir-170426132038275.html|archive-date=September 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Censorship on Facebook increases 19% in 6 months in 2014; India leads the list of content removal.<ref>{{Cite book|title=India Digital Review|last=Business Insights|publisher=|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe Indian government also imposed a six-month ban on Facebook, Twitter, and other social networking sites in Kashmir Valley in 2016-17, due to public safety because the Indian government believed social media were being misused by anti-national and anti-social elements backed by [[Pakistan Army]] and Pakistan intelligence agencies including [[Inter-Services Intelligence]]. The ban was also placed to cut communication between the terrorists, who were countering the efforts made by the [[Indian Army]].\n\n===Iran===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Iran}}\nAfter the [[Iran elections 2009|2009 election in Iran]], the website was banned because of fears that opposition movements were being organized on the website.<ref name=\"iran and iraq\"/>  However, after four years of the blocking of Facebook website, as of September 2013, the blocking of both Twitter and Facebook was thought to have been lifted without notice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mashable.com/2013/09/16/twitter-facebook-iran/|title=Iran Unblocks Twitter and Facebook|date=August 17, 2013|accessdate=August 17, 2013|agency=[[Mashable]]|work=Chris Taylor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829214714/http://mashable.com/2013/09/16/twitter-facebook-iran/|archive-date=August 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\nIranians lost unrestricted access to Facebook and Twitter the next day, leaving many people wondering whether the opening was deliberate or the result of some technical glitch.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/18/world/middleeast/facebook-and-twitter-blocked-again-in-iran-after-respite.html | work=The New York Times | first=Thomas | last=Erdbrink | title=Iran Bars Social Media Again After a Day | date=September 17, 2013 | access-date=February 21, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301180901/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/18/world/middleeast/facebook-and-twitter-blocked-again-in-iran-after-respite.html | archive-date=March 1, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\nIn September 2016, the [[Israeli government|Cabinet of Israel]] has said to have agreed with Facebook to remove content that is deemed as incitement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/sep/12/facebook-israel-monitor-posts-incite-violence-social-media?CMP=twt_gu|title=Facebook and Israel to work to monitor posts that incite violence|date=2016-12-09|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=2018-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104073223/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/sep/12/facebook-israel-monitor-posts-incite-violence-social-media?CMP=twt_gu|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/12/30/facebook-says-it-is-deleting-accounts-at-the-direction-of-the-u-s-and-israeli-governments/|title=Facebook Says It Is Deleting Accounts at the Direction of the U.S. and Israeli Governments|date=2016-12-09|website=The Intercept|access-date=2018-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103225231/https://theintercept.com/2017/12/30/facebook-says-it-is-deleting-accounts-at-the-direction-of-the-u-s-and-israeli-governments/|archive-date=2018-01-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/09/12/facebook-is-collaborating-with-the-israeli-government-to-determine-what-should-be-censored/|title=Facebook is collaborating with the Israeli government to determine what should be censored|date=2017-12-30|website=The Intercept|access-date=2018-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104192338/https://theintercept.com/2016/09/12/facebook-is-collaborating-with-the-israeli-government-to-determine-what-should-be-censored/|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> Israel has one of the most openly cooperative relationships with Facebook and the Israeli Justice Ministery boasted that Facebook had removed 95 percent of its requested content.<ref name=\"Taibbi\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/who-will-fix-facebook-759916/|title=Who Will Fix Facebook?|last=Taibbi|first=Matt|last2=Taibbi|first2=Matt|date=2018-11-26|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070635/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/who-will-fix-facebook-759916/|archive-date=2019-05-10|url-status=live}}</ref> This announcement came after top Facebook officials met with the Israeli government to determine which Facebook accounts should be deleted on the grounds that they constituted as incitement. The [[Israel]]i interior minister's office has said that they agreed with Facebook representatives to create teams that would figure out how best to monitor and remove \"inflammatory content\" online.\n\nAhead of municipal elections in 2018, Israel\u2019s National Cyber Directorate has stated that Facebook was banning \"thousands\" of accounts ahead of the elections. Critics of Israel\u2019s policies are not happy with this move as they claim this is being used as a way to silence outspoken [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] civilians, activists and journalists. The activists argue that when they post material meant to critique [[Palestinian territories|the occupation]], Israel sees it as encouraging violence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/palestinian-activists-facebook_us_57ed66bce4b082aad9ba1122|title=Palestinian Activists Are Angry About Alleged Facebook Censorship|date=2016-09-29|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115141659/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/palestinian-activists-facebook_us_57ed66bce4b082aad9ba1122|archive-date=2018-01-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Some believe that the Israeli government and Facebook have an \"informal arrangement\" for monitoring Facebook content. Jordana Cutler, who previously was the [[Chief of staff|Chief of Staff]] at the [[Embassy of Israel in Washington, D.C.|Israel Embassy in Washington DC]] and a former adviser to Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] is Facebook\u2019s head of policy in Israel. She claimed that Facebook is merely following suggestions. \u201cWe receive requests from the government but are not committed to them,\u201d Cutler said.<ref name=\"Taibbi\"/>\n\n===North Korea===\n{{main|Internet in North Korea}}\nIn April 2016, North Korea started blocking Facebook, \"a move underscoring its concern with the spread of online information,\" according to [[The Associated Press]]. Anyone who tries to access it without special permission from the North Korean government, will be subject to punishment.<ref name=NK>{{Cite web| title = North Korea blocks Facebook, Twitter and YouTube| work = [[The Associated Press]]| date = 4 April 2016| accessdate = 4 April 2016| url = http://globalnews.ca/news/2616449/north-korea-blacks-facebook-twitter-and-youtube/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160406095746/http://globalnews.ca/news/2616449/north-korea-blacks-facebook-twitter-and-youtube/| archive-date = 6 April 2016| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n===Malaysia===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Malaysia}}\nFacebook was blocked for a few days in [[Malaysia]] during the [[2011 Egyptian protests]].<ref name=\"inaccessible in Egypt\"/>\n\n===Mauritius===\nThe Information and Communication Technologies Authority (ICTA) of [[Mauritius]], ordered [[Internet Service Provider|internet service providers]] of the country to ban [[Facebook]] on immediate effect, on the 8 November 2007 because of a fake profile page of the Prime Minister. Access to Facebook was restored on the next day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.noulakaz.net/weblog/2007/11/08/facebook-a-mauritian-tragedy/ |title=Facebook: A Mauritian tragedy? |publisher=Noulakaz |date=2007-11-08 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723230916/http://www.noulakaz.net/weblog/2007/11/08/facebook-a-mauritian-tragedy/ |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pascalg.wordpress.com/2007/11/08/facebook-outage-in-mauritius-its-been-censored/ |title=Facebook outage in Mauritius \u2013 it's been censored!!! &#124; Sometimes life is good... |publisher=Pascalg.wordpress.com |date=2007-11-08 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824024531/http://pascalg.wordpress.com/2007/11/08/facebook-outage-in-mauritius-its-been-censored/ |archive-date=2011-08-24 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexpress.mu/services/archive-97239-maurice-censure-le-site-communautaire-facebook.html|title=Maurice censure le site communautaire Facebook|publisher=L'express|accessdate=9 Nov 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120913202342/http://www.lexpress.mu/services/archive-97239-maurice-censure-le-site-communautaire-facebook.html|archivedate=2012-09-13}}</ref>\n\n===Morocco===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Morocco}}\nOn February 5, 2008, [[Fouad Mourtada]], a citizen of Morocco, was arrested for 43 days due to the alleged creation of a faked Facebook profile of [[Prince Moulay Rachid of Morocco]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/02/07/morocco.facebook/index.html?eref=rss_latest|title=Police arrest man for 'villainous' theft of prince's ID on Facebook|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 5, 2008|date=February 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215102125/http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/02/07/morocco.facebook/index.html?eref=rss_latest|archive-date=February 15, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/07/world/africa/07briefs-identity.html?ex=1360040400&en=28cce9bbc525d4cd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|title=Moroccan held for alleged royal ID theft|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=March 5, 2008|date=February 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215102635/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/07/world/africa/07briefs-identity.html?ex=1360040400&en=28cce9bbc525d4cd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|archive-date=February 15, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan===\nOn May 19, 2010, [[Lahore High Court]] ordered Facebook to be blocked. Facebook was blocked until May 31 after a competition page encouraged users to post drawings of The Holy Prophet Hazrat Mohammad SAW. The controversial page named \u201cDraw Mohammad SAW Day\u201d had been created by a Facebook user in response to American cartoonist Molly Noris\u2019s protest to the decision of US television channel, Comedy Central to cancel an episode of the popular show \u201cSouth Park\u201d over its depiction of Mohammed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/pakistan/7740295/Facebook-blocked-in-Pakistan-over-Prophet-Mohammed-cartoon-row.html|title=Facebook blocked in Pakistan over Prophet Mohammed cartoon row|last=Crilly|first=Rob|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=19 May 2010|work=|access-date=31 May 2019|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100520031525/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/pakistan/7740295/Facebook-blocked-in-Pakistan-over-Prophet-Mohammed-cartoon-row.html|archive-date=20 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Noris had however disavowed having declared May 20 \u201cDraw Muhammad Day\u201d and had condemned the effort and issued an apology. The ban, implemented by the [[Pakistan Telecommunication Authority]], also resulted in a ban on YouTube and restricted access to other websites, including Wikipedia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/may/31/pakistan-lifts-facebook-ban|title=Pakistan lifts Facebook ban but 'blasphemous' pages stay hidden|last=Walsh|first=Declan|date=31 May 2010|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 May 2019|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531090225/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/may/31/pakistan-lifts-facebook-ban|archive-date=31 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 2017, the [[NetBlocks]] internet shutdown observatory and [[Digital Rights Foundation]] collected evidence of nationwide blocking of Facebook alongside other social media services, imposed by the government in response to the violent [[2017 Tehreek-e-Labaik protest|Tehreek-e-Labaik protests]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://digitalrightsfoundation.pk/press-release-drf-and-netblocks-find-blanket-and-nation-wide-ban-on-social-media-in-pakistan-and-demand-it-to-be-lifted-immediately/|title=DRF and NetBlocks find blanket and nation-wide ban on social media in Pakistan and demand it to be lifted immediately|date=2017-11-26|work=Digital Rights Foundation|access-date=2017-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040815/https://digitalrightsfoundation.pk/press-release-drf-and-netblocks-find-blanket-and-nation-wide-ban-on-social-media-in-pakistan-and-demand-it-to-be-lifted-immediately/|archive-date=2017-12-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nation.com.pk/27-Nov-2017/activists-assail-blanket-ban-on-social-media|title=Activists assail blanket ban on social media|date=2017-11-27|work=The Nation|access-date=2017-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128200108/http://nation.com.pk/27-Nov-2017/activists-assail-blanket-ban-on-social-media|archive-date=2017-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/social-buzz/2017/11/need-know-nation-wide-internet-disruptions-dharna/|title=All you need to know about nation-wide internet disruptions during dharna|date=2017-11-27|website=Samaa TV|access-date=2017-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127185835/https://www.samaa.tv/social-buzz/2017/11/need-know-nation-wide-internet-disruptions-dharna/|archive-date=2017-11-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The technical investigation found that all major Pakistani fixed-line and mobile service providers were affected by the restrictions, which were lifted by the PTA the next day when protests abated following the resignation of [[Minister for Law and Justice (Pakistan)|Minister for Law and Justice]] [[Zahid Hamid]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nation.com.pk/26-Nov-2017/the-issue-of-social-media-networking|title=The issue of social media networking|date=2017-11-26|work=The Nation|access-date=2017-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128200126/http://nation.com.pk/26-Nov-2017/the-issue-of-social-media-networking|archive-date=2017-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Other websites including Twitter, YouTube and Dailymotion were also reportedly blocked by order of the PTA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ifex.org/pakistan/2017/11/28/tv-news-suspended/|title=Pakistan suspends TV news channels and social media sites to block protest coverage|publisher=ifex|date=29 November 2017|access-date=29 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129095415/https://ifex.org/pakistan/2017/11/28/tv-news-suspended/|archive-date=29 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\nIn 2014, Russia demanded that all links on Facebook be blocked that supported Russian opposition Aleksei A. Navalny. Facebook users were blocked from any protest supporting Aleksei.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Facebook should Stop Cooperating with Russian Government Censorship.|last=Somin|first=llya|publisher=Washington: WP Company LLC d/b/a The Washington Post|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> This included about ten million Facebook users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/02/business/international/web-freedom-is-seen-to-be-growing-as-a-global-issue-in-2015.html|title=Web Freedom Is Seen as a Growing Global Issue|last=Goel|first=Vindu|date=2015-01-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-10|last2=Kramer|first2=Andrew E.|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070628/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/02/business/international/web-freedom-is-seen-to-be-growing-as-a-global-issue-in-2015.html|archive-date=2019-05-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Sri Lanka===\n{{main|Censorship in Sri Lanka}}\nIn March 2018, Facebook was blocked for 3 days in [[Sri Lanka]] due to racial hate speeches being rumored around the country via the social media which caused many riots in the country by extremist groups. However this decision was not permanent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Tense-situ-in-Teldeniya-over-death-of-assault-victim-146768.html|title=Tense situ in Teldeniya over death of assault victim|publisher=|access-date=2018-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315003725/http://www.dailymirror.lk/article/Tense-situ-in-Teldeniya-over-death-of-assault-victim-146768.html|archive-date=2018-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"guard\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/14/facebook-accused-by-sri-lanka-of-failing-to-control-hate-speech |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=Sri Lanka accuses Facebook over hate speech after deadly riots |first=Michael |last=Safi |date=March 14, 2018 |quote=As mobs of hardline Buddhists rioted and lit fires in towns in the central district of Kandy, Facebook, WhatsApp and several other platforms were blocked across the country [...] Both Facebook and WhatsApp remain restricted but the Guardian understands the block on the latter could be lifted by Wednesday evening.}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2019, Facebook was blocked along with other social media sites until April 30, 2019 in [[Sri Lanka]] to prevent the false information about [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings|Easter Sunday bombings]] spreading around the country via the social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/04/21/sri-lanka-bans-social-media-after-bombings|title=Sri Lanka temporarily bans social media after terrorist bombings|website=engadget.com|date=April 21, 2019|access-date=April 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502222749/https://www.engadget.com/2019/04/21/sri-lanka-bans-social-media-after-bombings/|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/30/social-media-ban-lifted|title=Social media ban lifted|publisher=Newsfirst.lk|date=April 30, 2019|access-date=April 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430053155/https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/30/social-media-ban-lifted/|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2019, the [[Sri Lanka]]n government has reimposed a ban on social media platforms in an effort to stop the spread of rumours after violence erupted between groups of civilians in Negombo, north of the capital and site of one of the [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings|Easter Sunday bombings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sri-lanka-blasts-curfew/sri-lanka-imposes-curfew-in-negombo-after-clashes-bans-social-media-idUSL3N22H0EF|title=Sri Lanka imposes curfew in Negombo after clashes, bans social media|publisher=Reuters.com|date=May 5, 2019|access-date=May 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505193610/https://www.reuters.com/article/sri-lanka-blasts-curfew/sri-lanka-imposes-curfew-in-negombo-after-clashes-bans-social-media-idUSL3N22H0EF|archive-date=May 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban was lifted on May 6, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/May06_1557116757CH.php|title=Temporary ban on social media platforms lifted|publisher=Colombopage.com|date=May 6, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513034310/http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/May06_1557116757CH.php|archive-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2019, the [[Sri Lanka]]n government temporarily banned social media including Facebook. This measure has been taken owing to the false propaganda carried out by the social media and the unrest which had occurred in several areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/55087/social-media-temporarily-banned|title=Social media temporarily banned|publisher=AdaDerana.lk|date=May 13, 2019|access-date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513034950/http://www.adaderana.lk/news/55087/social-media-temporarily-banned|archive-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The ban was lifted on May 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adaderana.lk/news/55200/social-media-ban-in-sri-lanka-lifted|title=Social media ban in Sri Lanka lifted|publisher=AdaDerana.lk|date=May 17, 2019|access-date=May 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518205447/https://www.adaderana.lk/news/55200/social-media-ban-in-sri-lanka-lifted|archive-date=May 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Sudan===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Sudan}}\nIn December 2018, the [[Sudan]]ese government blocked Facebook, along with other [[social media]] sites, which were being used by anti-government protesters to organize [[Sudanese protests (2018\u201319)|protests against President Omar al-Bashir]].<ref name=\"netblocks.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/social-media-access-restored-across-sudan-noy9dnB3|title=Social media access restored across Sudan|date=2019-02-26|website=[[NetBlocks]]|access-date=2019-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043048/https://netblocks.org/reports/social-media-access-restored-across-sudan-noy9dnB3|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sudan-protests-internet-idUSKCN1OW0Z7|title=Sudan restricts social media access to counter protest movement|date=2019-01-02|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306111406/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sudan-protests-internet-idUSKCN1OW0Z7|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://qz.com/africa/1510229/sudan-shuts-down-facebook-twitter-instagram-amid-bread-protests/ |title=Sudan has blocked Facebook, Twitter and Instagram to counter anti-govt protests |access-date=2018-12-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228235548/https://qz.com/africa/1510229/sudan-shuts-down-facebook-twitter-instagram-amid-bread-protests/ |archive-date=2018-12-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> The restrictions were lifted 68 days later following the introduction of emergency measures outlawing public demonstrations.<ref name=\"netblocks.org\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-sudan-protests-emergency-idUKKCN1QE26I|title=Sudan's Bashir bans protests in new emergency measures|date=2019-02-25|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306043806/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-sudan-protests-emergency-idUKKCN1QE26I|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Syria===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Syria}}\nThe Syrian government explained their ban by claiming the website promoted attacks on authorities.<ref name=\"syria\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSOWE37285020071123|title=Syria blocks Facebook in Internet crackdown|accessdate=March 5, 2008|author=Yacoub Oweis, Khaled|work=Reuters|date=November 23, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201114242/http://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSOWE37285020071123|archive-date=February 1, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Syrian-govt-blocks-use-of-Facebook| title=Syrian gov't blocks use of Facebook| work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]| date=November 24, 2007| accessdate=March 8, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301180845/http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Syrian-govt-blocks-use-of-Facebook| archive-date=March 1, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> The government also feared [[Mossad|Israeli]] infiltration of Syrian social networks on Facebook.<ref name=\"syria\" /> Facebook was also used by Syrian citizens to criticize the [[government of Syria]], as public criticism of the Syrian government used to be punishable by imprisonment.<ref name=\"syria\" /> In February 2011, Facebook was un-blocked from all ISP's and the website remains to be accessible.<ref>{{Citation\n| url = https://www.dawn.com/news/1320650\n| title = Tajikistan blocks Facebook access to silence critics\n| publisher = [[Reuters]]\n| location = International\n| date = November 27, 2012\n| access-date = November 7, 2017\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171107221944/https://www.dawn.com/news/1320650\n| archive-date = November 7, 2017\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n===Tajikistan===\nIn November 2012, [[Tajikistan]] blocked access to Facebook in response to comments posted online, spreading \u201cmud and slander\u201d about President [[Emomalii Rahmon]] and various other officials.<ref>{{Citation\n| url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/27/net-us-tajikistan-facebook-idUSBRE8AQ0JY20121127\n| title = Could it happen again? Remembering Pakistan's Facebook, YouTube ban\n| publisher = [[Dawn Media Group|Dawn]]\n| location = International\n| date = March 27, 2017\n| access-date = June 30, 2017\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172245/http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/27/net-us-tajikistan-facebook-idUSBRE8AQ0JY20121127\n| archive-date = September 24, 2015\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Thailand}}\nIn 2017, Thailand asked Facebook to remove 309 posted items that were said to be illegal by standards of Thailand. However, Facebook only deleted 178 of the items, leaving 131 still on Facebook. Thai authorities stated if they found any illegal content in the remaining 131 posts they would ban all 14.8 million users from Facebook, instead of taking legal action. All posts ended up being removed from Facebook, preventing the shutdown of Facebook in Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.ezp.mesacc.edu/login?qurl=http://link.galegroup.com%2fapps%2fdoc%2fA493945757%2fITOF%3fu%3dmcc_mesa%26sid%3dITOF%26xid%3d341adb3a|title=Off-Campus eResource Access - Paul A. Elsner Library @ Mesa Community College|website=login.ezp.mesacc.edu|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Tunisia ===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Tunisia}}\nFacebook was a major part of the political uprisings of the \u2018Arab Spring\u2019 in 2011.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aal|first=Konstantin|last2=Schorch|first2=Mar\u00e9n|last3=Elkilani|first3=Esma Ben Hadj|last4=Wulf|first4=Volker|date=2019-05-28|title=Facebook and the Mass Media in Tunisia|url=https://www001.zimt.uni-siegen.de/ojs/index.php/mia/article/view/36|journal=Media in Action|language=en|issue=1|pages=135\u2013168}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkey ===\n{{main|Internet regulation in Turkey}}\nAfter photos of Mehmet Selim Kiraz being held at gun point by two terrorists began circulation on social media on April 6, 2015, the Turkish government banned Facebook, Twitter, Youtube, and 166 other websites in the country for hours. The government does not tolerate \"anti-government propaganda,\" and their laws are becoming increasingly more strict. In the 2015 Press Freedom Index from Reporters Without Borders, Turkey ranked 149 of 180 countries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2015/0406/Turkey-turns-off-Twitter-and-Facebook-as-censorship-grows|title=Turkey turns off Twitter and Facebook as censorship grows|date=2015-04-06|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2019-05-10|issn=0882-7729|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510072126/https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2015/0406/Turkey-turns-off-Twitter-and-Facebook-as-censorship-grows|archive-date=2019-05-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\nFacebook was blocked at 11.30pm on Feb 27 2020, along with several other social media sites. It happened the day that the military crisis in Idlib escalated.<ref>https://netblocks.org/reports/social-media-blocked-in-turkey-as-idlib-military-crisis-escalates-r8VWGXA5</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{main|Internet censorship in the United Kingdom}}\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] on April 28, 2011, the day before the [[wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton]], a number of politically motivated Facebook groups and pages were removed or suspended from the website as part of a nationwide crackdown on political activity. The groups and pages were mostly concerned with opposition to government spending cuts, and many were used to organize demonstrations in a continuation of the [[2010 UK student protests]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/29/facebook-activist-pages-purged | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Shiv | last=Malik | title=Activists claim purge of Facebook pages | date=April 29, 2011 | access-date=December 17, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019200501/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/29/facebook-activist-pages-purged | archive-date=October 19, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Chan4News-29April2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/facebook-suspends-uk-activist-groups |title=Facebook 'suspends UK activist groups' - Channel 4 News |publisher=Channel4.com |date=2011-04-29 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903124202/http://www.channel4.com/news/facebook-suspends-uk-activist-groups |archive-date=2011-09-03 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-29April2011\">{{cite news | url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/29/facebook-deactivates-protest-pages-in-britain/ | work=The New York Times | first=Jennifer | last=Preston | title=Facebook Deactivates Protest Pages in Britain | date=April 29, 2011 | access-date=May 14, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503215815/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/29/facebook-deactivates-protest-pages-in-britain/ | archive-date=May 3, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref> The censorship of the pages coincided with a series of pre-emptive arrests of known activists.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/29/royal-wedding-police-criticised-protesters | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Robert | last1=Booth | first2=Sandra | last2=Laville | first3=Shiv | last3=Malik | title=Royal wedding: police criticised for pre-emptive strikes against protesters | date=April 29, 2011 | access-date=December 17, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005100702/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/apr/29/royal-wedding-police-criticised-protesters | archive-date=October 5, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> Amongst the arrestees were a communist and socialist, and a few members of a street theater group planning an [[effigy]] beheading performance in opposition to the monarchy.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-13234682 | work=BBC News | title=Royal wedding: Three held over effigy beheading claims | date=April 29, 2011 | access-date=July 21, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221135142/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-13234682 | archive-date=December 21, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA Facebook spokesman said the pages were disabled as part of a routine sweep because they were created with fake personal profiles, a violation of the company\u2019s term of service. In this case a number of the Facebook personal profile pages represented causes, rather than real people. Facebook \"offered to help convert the profiles to pages that are designed to represent companies, groups or causes.\"<ref name=\"NYT-29April2011\"/> The spokesman went on to say that \"the Met Police did not ask Facebook to take down this content.\"<ref name=\"Chan4News-29April2011\"/>\n\nIn March 2018, far-right [[Britain First]] was removed by Facebook. The pages of the leaders of the party were also taken down following their arrest and incarceration.\n\n===Vietnam===\n{{main|Internet censorship in Vietnam}}\nFacebook was blocked in Vietnam for two weeks in May 2016 due to [[protest]] of dissidents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/17/facebook-blocked-in-vietnam-over-the-weekend-due-to-citizen-protests/|title=Facebook blocked in Vietnam over the weekend due to citizen protest|work=TechCrunch|accessdate=May 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206073825/https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/17/facebook-blocked-in-vietnam-over-the-weekend-due-to-citizen-protests/|archive-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVietnam Facebook users total about 52 million and is a vital tool for their day to day use. However, the government is not accountable to the people which causes abuse of censorship in Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite book|title=How Facebook is damaging freedom of expression in Vietnam|last=Khoi|first=M|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In 2018, the government created a huge military unit to block posts containing \"wrong views\" online. To appease the government, Facebook removed 160 \"toxic\" accounts for speech against the Communist Party in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/theworldpost/wp/2018/02/19/vietnam-internet/|title=Vietnam's Internet is in trouble|last=Luong|first=Dien|date=February 19, 2018|website=The Washington Post|access-date=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070651/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/theworldpost/wp/2018/02/19/vietnam-internet/|archive-date=May 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Criticism of Facebook#Censorship controversies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist| 30em}}\n\n{{Censorship and websites}}\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{Internet censorship circumvention technologies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Censorship of Facebook}}\n[[Category:Internet censorship by organization|Facebook]]\n[[Category:Facebook]]\n[[Category:Facebook criticisms and controversies]]\n[[Category:Internet censorship in China]]\n[[Category:Censorship]]\n", "name_user": "Can I Log In", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBangladesh:inline notes after punctuations please", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Censorship_of_Facebook"}
{"title_page": "Takuya Sugi", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese professional wrestler + Snitch}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name= Takuya Sugi\n|image= Sugi - Lucha Libre - Japan Expo 2011 - P1210485 Crop.jpg\n|caption= Sugi in July 2011\n|names= Sugi San<br>'''Sugi'''<br>El Blazer<br />Yoshitsune<br />Shanao<br />Mini Cima<br />Little Dragon <br />Hustle Kamen Ranger Red<br />Michinoku Ranger Gold<br />Ahii<br />The\u2605Zest (2nd generation)<br />Namazu Man<br />Rabbit Boy<br />Super Milo<br />Uwai #32<br />NOIZ<br />El Fuerte\n|height={{convert|1.63|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}<!-- In Japan they measure height in meters so that should be first -->\n|weight={{convert|65|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<!--In Japan they measure weight in kilograms so that should be first -->\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1983|10|6|mf=y}} \n|death_date = \n|birth_place = [[Shizuoka City]], Japan\n|resides=\n|billed= Hustle Nebula (as Hustle Kamen Ranger Red)<br />[[Hiraizumi, Iwate|Hiraizumi]] (as Shanao/Yoshitsune)\n|trainer=[[\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n]]<br />[[Jorge Rivera (wrestler)|Jorge \"Skayde\" Rivera]]\n|debut= May 11, 2003\n|retired=\n|}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Takuya Sugi'''|\u6749\u5353\u4e5f|Sugi Takuya}}<ref name=Puro>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresucentral.com/yoshitsune.html|title=Profile at Puroresu Central|publisher=Puroresu Central|accessdate=2012-01-15}}</ref> is a Japanese [[professional wrestler]] from [[Shizuoka City|Shizuoka]]. He is currently signed to [[Pro Wrestling Zero1]], where he works as '''Sugi''' (stylized in all capital letters). He has used many aliases, most commonly '''Yoshitsune''' and '''Sugi'''. He is mainly known for his high-flying abilities.\n\n==Career==\n===Toryumon (2002\u20132004)===\nImmediately after graduating in the 11th Toryumon school class term, Sugi debuted in 2003 in [[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon Mexico]], shortly after moving to the [[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon X]] brand. He went under the [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|gimmick]] of '''{{Nihongo|Mini Cima|\u30df\u30cbCIMA|Mini Cima}}''', a lighter version of the popular Toryumon wrestler [[Nobuhiko Oshima|Cima]], who was a part of the Mini Crazy Max [[Stable (professional wrestling)|stable]] along with [[Kagetora|Suwacito]] and [[Masaki Okimoto|Small Dandy Fuji]]. Aligning themselves as [[Tweener (professional wrestling)|tweeners]], they got into a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[BabyFace (professional wrestling)|babyface]] faction Sailor Boys ([[Taiji Ishimori]], [[Brahman Brothers|Kei Sato and Shu Sato]]), having several matches against them, sometimes accompanied by senior members of the actual Crazy Max.\n\nIn December 2003, Mini Cima and his team competed in the ''Young Dragons Cup 2003'' scramble match, but they were unable to win, being [[Takeshi Minamino]] the eventual tournament winner. They would be more successful at the ''Yamaha Cup 2004''tag team tournament, with Mini Cima and Suwacito defeating [[Manabu Murakami (wrestler)|Manabu Murakami]] and [[Naoki Tanizaki]] in the first round and the Sailor Boys in the second to crown themselves as winners. On September 9, 2003 the group competed in an elimination match for the [[UWA World Welterweight Championship]], eliminating the team of Los Carros Ex\u00f3ticos (Gallardo, Lambo Miura and Murcielago) before falling short to Los Salseros Japoneses (Minamino, [[Kenichi Sakai|Pineapple Hanai]] and [[Takayasu Fukuda|Mango Fukuda]]). This was the Toryumon X final event, with the promotion folding shortly after. Mini Crazy Max had its last reunion in the special event Dragon Fire The Final Challenge on October 14, where they competed in another special challenge match.\n\n===Hustle (2004\u20132006)===\nIn September 2004, still based on Toryumon, Sugi and his partners started wrestling for the [[Hustle (professional wrestling)|Hustle]] promotion. They appeared as the Hustle Kamen Rangers, a ''[[Power Rangers]]''-inspired [[super sentai]] stable which was a special division of the Hustle Army led by top babyface [[Naoya Ogawa]]. Sugi himself played '''{{Nihongo|Hustle Kamen Red|\u30cf\u30c3\u30b9\u30eb\u4eee\u9762\u30ec\u30c3\u30c9|Hassuru Kamen Reddo}}''' (a role formerly played by [[Masaki Okimoto]]), teaming up with [[Masaki Okimoto|Hustle Kamen Blue]] and [[Takayasu Fukuda|Hustle Kamen Yellow]] as a power trio. They competed in the undercard of events against villainous characters from the [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] Takada Monster Army commanded by [[Nobuhiko Takada|Generalissimo Takada]]; their usual opponents were [[Brahman Brothers|Devil Pierroth I & Devil Pierroth II]], whom they defeated in many occasions.\n\nIn the event Hustle House Vol.10, held on October 27, 2005, Hustle Kamen Rangers were defeated by [[Brahman Brothers|Demon Spider Blue, Demon Spider Yellow]] and [[Taiji Ishimori|Riser Glen]], being the latter in storyline a character come from the TV [[tokusatsu]] series ''Phantom Star God Justirisers'', only brainwashed to serve the Monster Army. In order to counter him, Hustle Kamen Rangers introduced another character from said series, [[Kota Ibushi|Liosazer]], who helped them to defeat the heel stable at the Hustlemania 2005 event and turn Riser again to good. The rangers would still competing for Hustle, being later opposed by an [[itako]] wrestler named Kyou Itako.\n\nOn February 10, 2006, the Monster Army introduced a cadre of [[Evil twin|evil clones]] of the Hustle Kamen Rangers, called the Monster Kamen Rangers. They consistently defeated Sugi and his team, forcing them to introduce a new member, [[Kota Ibushi|Hustle Kamen Orange]], in order to get the first win against the villains. The win was short-lived, however, as the Monster Kamen Rangers defeated them again, and this time kidnapped Hustle Kamen Yellow in order to [[brainwash]] him. Now with Yellow as an enemy, Red and new member Hustle Kamen Green attempted to reason with him, but they were beaten when Yellow pinned Red. The storyline continued until Hustlemania 2006, where they finally managed to bring Yellow back and defeat the Monster Kamen Rangers for good. The team then announced they would travel to the stars in order to defend the peace and justice beyond Hustle, ceasing their apparitions from the promotion.\n\n===Michinoku Pro Wrestling (2004\u20132009)===\nSugi started wrestling for [[Michinoku Pro Wrestling]] in October 2004. He debuted during the ''Futaritabi Tag Team Tournament 2004'' under the gimmick of '''{{Nihongo|Michinoku Ranger Gold|MICHINOKU \u30ec\u30f3\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc\u91d1|Michinoku Renj\u0101 Kin}}''', a super sentai character similar to the one he played in Hustle. Teaming up with [[Masaki Okimoto|Michinoku Ranger Silver]], Sugi got important victories over [[Jinsei Shinzaki]] and [[Shinjitsu Nohashi]] and Los Salseros Japoneses, but they did not win the league. They kept their gimmicks until December, when Sugi adopted the gimmick of '''{{Nihongo|Shanao|\u906e\u90a3\u738b|Shanao}}''', a masked [[Buddhist monk|monk]] inspired on the historical [[Minamoto no Yoshitsune]]. Shanao would come to the ring carrying a [[katana]] and saying prayers, and drew popularity among the audience for his high-risk, aerial style of wrestling.\n[[File:FUKUMEN-MANIA2018022048.jpg|thumb|240px|SUGI in 2019.]]\nIn 2005, Shanao joined forces with the Sailor Boys (now composed solely by Kei and Shu Sato) to participate in the ''Michinoku Trios League'', being unsuccessful. The final night of the tournament, in which they had been eliminated by points, Shanao teamed up with his master, [[Yoshihiro Asai|The Tiger II]], to defeat [[Fumiyuki Hashimoto|Kagetora]] and [[Shinjitsu Nohashi]]. The alliance with the Sailor Boys lasted until mid-year, when Shanao formed a tag team with [[Masaki Okimoto|Rasse]]. He also had a brief tenure in the ''Tetsujin Tournament'', but he was forced to forfeit most of his matches due to an injury. Shanao returned on September 10 in a losing effort to Takeshi Minamino, but he got his revenge the same night, defeating Minamino and Los Salseros Japoneses along with Kagetora, [[Kazuya Yuasa|Gaina]] and [[Hayato Fujita]].\n\nKagetora and he eventually kept their alliance and participated in the ''Futaritabi Tag Team Tournament 2005'', winning the league after beating Los Salseros Japoneses again, but Kagetora suddenly turned [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] and attacked Shanao, going to form the villainous stable Stoned. Now back with Rasse, Shanao and he had a shot for the [[Tohoku Tag Team Championship]] held by [[The Great Sasuke]] and [[Dick Togo]], but despite their effort, they were beaten. Days after, Shanao announced he was going to perform a [[genpuku]] ceremony in order to advance in his career, which was officiated by [[Jinsei Shinzaki]]. Shanao then changed his name to '''{{Nihongo|Yoshitsune|\u7fa9\u7d4c|Yoshitsune}}''', openly showing his identity, and changed his outfit to a [[samurai]]-like attire in purple, red and golden. Yoshitsune had his first match teaming up with Shinzaki, who came dressed as [[Sait\u014d Musashib\u014d Benkei]], defeating Rasse and Garuda with his new Shura finishing maneuver.\n\nThe next year, Yoshitsune's fame allowed him a title match for the [[Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship]] against [[Taka Michinoku]], falling short in his challenge. Nonetheless, Yoshitsune allied with The Great Sasuke and the now babyface Los Salseros Japoneses to wage war against Stoned, exchanging wins with them. He performed a new title pursuit by taking part in a tournament for the Tohoku Tag Team Championship with [[Tsutomu Oosugi|Rei]] as his partner, losing to [[Makoto Oishi]] and [[Shiori Asahi]]; Yoshitsune took part in the 2006 edition of the ''Tetsujin Tournament'', but he had to relinquish it again due to an injury. Upon his recovering, Yoshitsune recruited Rasse to compete in the ''Futaritabi Tag Team Tournament 2006'', but success seemed to be away from him that year, as they were eliminated at the finals by Kei and Shu Sato.\n\nIn 2007, Yoshitsune qualified for the ''Fukumen World League'' by defeating [[Kenichi Sakai|Ken45\u00ba]] and Shinjitsu Nohashi in respective matches. During the tournament, he eliminated [[Tatsuhito Senga|Shibaten]] first and legendary [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] member [[Jyushin Thunder Liger]] second, but he eventually fell to Mexican representative [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]] thanks to an intervention by Atlantis's cornerman Ol\u00edmpico. Ended the league, Yoshitsune returned to his alliance with the home army and joined The Great Sasuke for the ''Futaritabi Tag Team League''; although Sasuke and him eliminated the team of Rasse and Kagetora, an injury to Sasuke obliged them to exit the tournament and allow their opponents to advance round. Stardom finally came to Yoshitsune on November, however, when defeated [[Osaka Pro Wrestling]] representative Gaina in a match for the Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship. Yoshitsune then would open 2008 becoming a double champion, when Sasuke returned from his injury and joined him to defeat Rasse and Kagetora for the title.\n\nSugi retained his titles for most of 2008, beating challengers like Rasse, Takeshi Minamino, Shinji Nohashi and [[Tigers Mask]], as well as the team of [[Mens Teioh]] and [[Shinobu Sugawara|Shinobu]]. However, he would get in a new feud when [[Hayato Fujita]] turned heel and formed the faction Kowloon with the remnants of Stoned. After months of warfare, Hayato challenged Sugi to a match for the Tohoku Junior Heavyweight title, and he won the bout and the championship in an upset. Only months after, Sasuke and Yoshitsune faced Kei and Shu Sato from Kowloon in a match to unify their tag team titles with the [[UWA World Tag Team Championship]], but they were defeated and lost the belts. Concluded his reigns, Yoshitsune announced his departure from Michinoku Pro and had his last match in March 2009.\n\n===Dragondoor and El Dorado Wrestling (2005\u20132007)===\nAlong with most of his Toryumon class, Sugi joined the Dragondoor promotion in July 2005. He was introduced in a [[Vignette (professional wrestling)|vignette]] by top babyface Taiji Ishimori, who described him as a close ally carrying the genes of [[\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n]]. As such, Sugi appeared as '''{{Nihongo|Little Dragon|\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3|Ritoru Doragon}}''', a character wearing a mask and suit patterned after Drag\u00f3n, very much like the wrestler [[Dragon Kid]] from rival promotion [[Dragon Gate (wrestling)|Dragon Gate]]. In his first match, Little Dragon teamed up with Ishimori and the rest of his allies, [[Kota Ibushi]] and [[Tsutomu Oosugi|Milanito Collection a.t.]], in a losing effort against the popular stable Aagan Iisou ([[Shuji Kondo]], [[Yasushi Tsujimoto|Yasshi]] and [[Takuya Sugawara]]). His next and last high level match in the short-lived promotion would be at the final event, fighting with Ishimori against Stoned ([[Brahman Brothers|Kei Sato and Shu Sato]]), being defeated after an intervention by [[KAGETORA (wrestler)|Kagetora]] and [[Manabu Murakami (wrestler)|Maguro Ooma]]. Dragondoor closed shortly after.\n\nWhen the promotion was reopened as El Dorado Wrestling in April 2006, Sugi returned with the rest of wrestlers. This time he took the gimmick of '''{{Nihongo|El Blazer|\u30a8\u30eb\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30b6\u30fc|Eru Bureiz\u0101}}''', a mysterious, [[phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]]-like character in a gold and blue armored outfit. Blazer formed a tag team with Milanito Collection a.t. and took part in the very first match of the promotion, getting a victory over Kei and Shu Sato. They later avenged their defeats to Aagan Iisou by beating them with Kota Ibushi's aid, and also took another victory before Stoned in a [[Global Professional Wrestling Alliance]] event along with [[Jumping Kid Okimoto]]. In December 2006, the trio split up to compete in the ''Treasure Hunters Tag Tournament 2006'', with Ibushi teaming up with [[Milano Collection A.T.]] while Blazer stayed in Milanito's side; Sugi and his ally were defeated, and Milano and Kota advanced round before being eliminated by Dick Togo and Shuji Kondo at the finals. Milanito and Blazer, however, won the reserve bout of the tournament, defeating the Sato brothers through an intervention of a now unaligned Kagetora. In Sugi's last match in the promotion, he teamed up with Milano and Milanito to defeat a Stoned cell aided by [[Harashima]]. Blazer then announced he went freelance, and put an official end to his team with Milanito, leaving El Dorado.\n\n===All Japan Pro Wrestling (2006\u20132008)===\nOn August 20, 2006, Sugi made his first apparition in [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]] playing the character of '''Ahii''', the result of a cooperation between [[Sanrio|Sanrio Company Ltd.]] and AJPW. He was introduced by [[Keiji Mutoh]], and revealed himself as a strange character wearing a demonic-looking orange and black full body suit which represented the Mexican [[Habanero]] chili pepper. He made his first in-ring work the same night, entering after the main event to save Mutoh, [[Masanobu Fuchi]] and [[Kaz Hayashi]] from an attack by the [[Voodoo Murders]], and his official debut one day later, defeating VM member [[Fumiyuki Hashimoto|Voodoo Mask]]. Ahii remained as an ally to Mutoh and his babyface wrestlers against Voodoo Murders until November, when he got his own opponents in the form of [[Takayasu Fukuda|Mastodon]] and [[Takeshi Minamino|Tow Van John]], two personal enemies of his. Their enmity would be resolved on February 17, 2007, when Ahii defeated them both in a handicap match with the aid of his storyline brother, a green version of Ahii (played by [[Masaki Okimoto]]).\n\nSugi returned to AJPW on February 15, 2008 for a special event copromoted with [[Playboy]]. He played the one night gimmick of '''{{Nihongo|Rabbit Boy|\u30e9\u30d3\u30c3\u30c8\u30fb\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4|Rabitto B\u014di}}''', a character wearing a [[rabbit]] mask and a black playboy jacket. In his only apparition, Rabbit Boy defeated [[Masaki Okimoto|Giant Jet]].\n\nOn December 23, Sugi made his last apparition for AJPW for another one night character, this time as part of AJPW's usual copromotions with [[A Bathing Ape]]. Sugi portrayed '''Super Milo''', a [[monkey]] [[superhero]] wearing in green and yellow, and teamed up with [[Mitsunobu Kikuzawa|Teriyaki Boy]] to defeat Ebessan III and [[Kuishinbo Kamen]] in a comedy match.\n\n===Independent circuit (2006\u20132009)===\n[[File:FUKUMEN-MANIA2018022152.jpg|thumb|240px|SUGI along with Mr. Cacao (center) and El Hornet (right) in 2019.]]\nHe also appeared as Yoshitsune in some shows of Big Mouth LOUD and several others Japanese independent promotions, including the [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] LOCK UP sub-brand.\n\nSugi continued using the El Blazer gimmick as his main freelancing character. El Blazer then turned to a comedic character prone to mysteriously faint at his entrance, and had an appearance in [[Dramatic Dream Team]]'s brand ''Cruiser's Game'' wrestling against [[Kyohei Mikami|Mikami]] after ([[kayfabe]]) having been smoking [[marijuana]].\n\nSoon after becoming a freelancer, Sugi continued appearing randomly in several Japanese promotions as El Blazer, including [[Inoki Genome Federation|IGF]].\n\nStarting from June 3, 2007, Sugi appears in [[Kensuke Office]] as '''Namazu Man''' (\u306a\u307e\u305a\u30de\u30f3, \"Catfish Man\"). Shortly after, Namazu Man started to be played by another wrestler.\n\nAnother gimmick he used in 2007 is '''UWAI # 32''', a robot character only used in UWAI Station.\n\nOn December 29, 2008, Sugi appeared in an Akiba Pro Wrestling event as '''El Fuerte''' (\u30a8\u30eb\u30fb\u30d5\u30a9\u30eb\u30c6), a character inspired from the [[Street Fighter (video game)|Street Fighter]] video game saga.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.famitsu.com/game/news/1221018_1124.html | script-title=ja:\u30bd\u30ea\u30c3\u30c9\u30fb\u30b9\u30cd\u30fc\u30af\u304c\u7121\u7dda\u3067\u6307\u793a\uff01\uff1f \u30a2\u30ad\u30d0\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u7b2c2\u5f3e\u201c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30ea\u30df\u30c3\u30af\u30b9 \u6e7e\u5cb8\u6709\u660e\u5371\u6a5f\u4e00\u9aea\uff01\u201d\u304c\u958b\u50ac | date=2008-12-29 | accessdate=2016-10-04 |work=Famitsu.com | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n===Pro Wrestling Zero1 (2007\u20132009)===\nSugi started wrestling for [[Pro Wrestling Zero1-Max]] in May 2007 under his El Blazer character. After an unsuccessful battle royal match for the [[AWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship]], which was won by [[Dick Togo]], Blazer aligned himself under [[Masato Tanaka]]'s Sword Army, getting in battles against [[Takao Omori]]'s Axe Army. He got a shot at the [[ZERO1-MAX International Junior Heavyweight Championship]] held by Dragon Gate wrestler [[Masaaki Mochizuki]], but he was unsuccessful. Mochizuki offered him to team up and invited him to his promotion.\n\nFor most of his tenure in the company, however, Sugi ditched his Blazer identity and played a new character, '''The\u2606ZEST''', sponsored by the homonymous Japanese [[pachinko]] company. The gimmick had been played before by the wrestler Kamikaze, and would be played again by him later. On July 24, Zest won the WWA Junior Lightweight Championship by beating Osamu Namiguchi, and retained him until April 6, when Sugi relinquished both the character and the title and adopted yet a new gimmick, '''Noiz''', sponsored by rock band [[UchuSentai:Noiz]]. Now as Noiz, Sugi defeated Kamikaze as Zest and won again the championship. NOIZ also inherited Blazer's loyalty to Masato Tanaka, wrestling for him occasionally, and retained the title before Osamu Namiguchi before vacating him upon his departure from Zero1.\n\n===Dragon Gate (2008)===\nBlazer originally debuted in Dragon Gate on March 2008 as a Zero1 representative, but he was in storyline recognized by [[Kenichiro Arai]] as a Toryumon graduate. Blazer's first match was a special tag team with [[Ben Satterly|Pac]] against Tozawa-juku (Arai and [[Taku Iwasa]]), but he also aided New Hazard ([[BxB Hulk]] and [[Shinobu Sugawara|Shinobu]]) in the Mochizuki Buyuden events and Typhoon ([[Anthony W. Mori]] and [[Cima (wrestler)|Cima]]) against the [[Muscle Outlaw'z]]. In April, Blazer took part in a tournament for the [[Open the Brave Gate Championship]], eliminating Genki Horiguchi but being eliminated himself by [[Gamma (wrestler)|Gamma]] following outside interference. After his unsuccessful feud with Muscle Outlaw'z, Blazer concluded his tenure in Dragon Gate forming an alliance with fellow outsiders [[Takeshi Minamino]] and [[Shinjitsu Nohashi]], defeating [[Hayato Fujita]], [[Munenori Sawa]] and Yuta Yoshikawa in Mochizuki Buyuden and WORLD-1 ([[Kzy|mcKZ]] & [[Naoki Tanizaki]]) & Super Shenlong in Dragon Gate NEX.\n\n===Pro Wrestling Guerrilla (2008)===\nSugi made his [[United States|America]]n debut (as El Blazer) for [[Pro Wrestling Guerrilla]] on May 17, 2008. Replacing [[Kota Ibushi]], he teamed with Kagetora on PWG's second annual ''DDT4'' tournament, defeating [[Scott Lost]] and [[Joey Ryan (wrestler)|Joey Ryan]] in the first round, but losing to the [[PWG World Tag Team Championship|PWG World Tag Team Champions]] [[Kevin Steen and El Generico]] in a title match in the next.\n\n===Lucha Libre AAA World Wide (2009\u20132012)===\nSugi signed up with [[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide]] in 2009 and made his return to M\u00e9xico, now under a modified, black and red version of his Yoshitsune outfit and the name of '''Sugi San''' (his last name followed by the [[Japanese honorifics|Japanese honorific -san]]). He was introduced by [[Kenzo Suzuki]] as a part of his [[heel (professional wrestling)|rudo]] stable La Yakuza, thus turning Sugi heel for the first time in his career. The faction, which also included [[El Oriental]], amassed a number of tag team wins until a match in [[Verano de Esc\u00e1ndalo (2009)|Verano de Esc\u00e1ndalo]], where they fell to [[The Psycho Circus]]. On August 30, Sugi competed individually in a [[Steel Cage Match]] where the last wrestler would be fired; Sugi escaped safely, but he got injured upon doing a theatrical backflip from the cage to the floor.\n[[File:Sugi.jpg|thumb|250px|Sugi in an AAA event.]]\nA month later, with La Yakuza dissolved and now unaligned, Sugi competed in a Five Way Ladder Match for the [[AAA World Cruiserweight Championship]] along with [[Extreme Tiger]], [[Jack Evans (wrestler)|Jack Evans]], [[Rocky Romero]] and [[Teddy Hart]], but he would be (kayfabe) injured by a piledriver by Hart and had to be stretchered out while Tiger won the title. After his return from the injury, Sugi took part in the ''Torneo Alas de Oro 2009'', leaving in second place along with [[Billy Boy]]. On October 9, Suzuki gathered La Yakuza again with [[Go Shiozaki]] replacing El Oriental to face Los Wagner Maniacos ([[Dr. Wagner Jr.]], [[Electroshock (wrestler)|Electroshock]] & [[\u00daltimo Gladiador]]), but they were defeated. Afterwards, Sugi announced his return to Japan, leaving AAA.\n\nAfter a year of hiatus, Sugi would compete in [[Pro Wrestling Noah]] as an AAA representative, now under the name of '''Sugi''' (in all caps), getting in a feud with [[Tatsuhito Senga|Ronin]] and [[Taiji Ishimori]]. He returned to M\u00e9xico along with Ronin, having touring matches against him, and finally coming back to TV as an unofficial member of [[Aero Star]]'s stable [[Real Fuerza Aerea]]. On June 28, Sugi and Ronin were sent to [[Paris, France]] in order to represent [[puroresu]] in the [[Japan Expo|Japan Expo 12th Impact]], returning to M\u00e9xico on July 5.\n\nOn July 9, 2012, Sugi held a press conference to announce his involvement in a conspiracy that had gotten [[Kazushige Nosawa]] and [[Io Shirai]] arrested for marijuana possession and smuggling. According to Sugi, Masahiro Hayashi, who worked as a liaison between AAA and Japan and had a personal grudge with Nosawa, promised him a contract extension with AAA in exchange for him planting the drugs on the couple.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://superluchas.com/sugi-san-confiesa-complot-en-contra-de-nosawa/ | title = Sugi San confiesa complot en contra de Nosawa. | author=Dark Angelita | date=2012-07-10 | accessdate=2012-07-10 | publisher=[[Super Luchas]] Magazine | language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Michinoku Pro Wrestling (2016)===\nFollowing the drug smuggling scandal, Sugi remained inactive for more than four years, with the exception of a single match held on November 18, 2015, when he faced [[Takeshi Minamino]] in an event held at [[Shinjuku Face]] to celebrate the 10th anniversary since his debut.\nAfter this long hiatus, Sugi returned to the ring for a charity event held on August 28, 2016, in support of the population hit by the [[2016 Kumamoto earthquakes|2016 Kumamoto earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://lineblog.me/mentaikid/archives/9986865.html | script-title=ja:\u30b9\u30bf\u30a4\u30eb\uff01 | date=2016-08-29 | accessdate=2016-10-06 |work=Mentai Kid Blog | language=Japanese}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, on September 16, he competed in a Michinoku Pro event for the first time in seven years, entering the 2016 Fukumen World League.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://battle-news.com/?p=23839 | script-title=ja:\u30ab\u30ea\u30b9\u30c6\u30a3\u30b3\uff08\u521d\u4ee3\u30df\u30b9\u30c6\u30a3\u30b3\uff09\u304c\u307f\u3061\u306e\u304f\u306e\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u306b\u51f1\u65cb\uff014\u5e74\u524d\u306e\u4e0d\u7965\u4e8b\u3067\u6d3b\u52d5\u3092\u4f11\u6b62\u3057\u3066\u3044\u305fSugi\u304c\u5fa9\u6d3b\uff01 | date=2016-09-17 | accessdate=2016-09-17 |work=Battle News | language=Japanese}}</ref> He defeated Leprechaun and Eisa8, but was eliminated by [[Car\u00edstico]] at the semi-finals.\n\n===Return to Zero1 (2017\u2013present)===\nAfter a few appearances in Pro Wrestling Land's End in 2017, Sugi returned to [[Pro Wrestling Zero1]] in August. He challenged unsuccessfully [[Kotaro Suzuki]] for the [[International Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|International Junior Heavyweight]] and [[NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship]]s, after which he declared he would challenge [[Ikuto Hidaka]] and [[Takuya Sugawara]] for the [[NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship]] with an unknown partner, which would revealed to be [[Psycho (wrestler)|Psycho]]. Sugi and him defeated Hidaka and Sugawara in a non-title match, but failed at taking the titles. Sugi replaced Psycho by Sean Guinness for the ''Furinkazan Tag Tournament 2017'', only to be eliminated in the first round by Hidaka and Sugawara again. He spent the next weeks teaming with several wrestlers against his old enemy faction [[Voodoo Murders]], until he announced [[Masamune (wrestler)|Masamune]] as his next tag team partner in his quest for the tag titles. On January 1, 2018, Sugi officially joined Zero1,<ref name=Zero1010118/> and the same day, he and Masamune won the NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship from Sugawara and Hidaka.<ref name=Zero1010118/>\n[[File:FUKUMEN-MANIA2018022147.jpg|thumb|250px|SUGI at the Fukumen Mania 2019.]]\nTheir reign ended in June, when Sugi and Masamune lost the titles to the new team of Ikuto Hidaka and Fuminori Abe. The same month, Sugi joined [[Kohei Sato]] and challenged [[Masato Tanaka]] and [[Yuji Hino]] for the [[NWA Intercontinental Tag Team Championship]], but they were defeated. He followed with a significantly successful tenure in the ''Fire Festival 2018'', scoring wins over Hino, [[Shinjiro Otani]] and [[Hiroshi Yamato]], though victory escaped his grasp again. In November, Sugi would prove better in the short ''Tenka-Ichi Junior Tournament 2018'' for the vacated [[International Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|International Junior Heavyweight Championship]] and [[NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship]], winning the tournament and the titles after beating [[Tatsuhito Takaiwa]], Asuka and [[Hayata (wrestler)|Hayata]]. Now as a champion, he resumed his team Kohei Sato to compete in the ''Furinkazan Tag Tournament 2018'', where they also won by defeating Chris Vice and [[Shogun Okamoto]] at the finals.\n\nSugi invested early 2019 in further championship pursuings. He retained his singles titles against Ikuto Hidaka, Shoki Kitamura and [[Tatsuhito Takaiwa]]. However, tag team titles remained away from him, with two failed challenges for the NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championships and NWA Intercontinental Tag Team Championships teaming up with [[Madoka (wrestler)|Hagane Shinnou]] and usual partner Sato respectively. In July, he participated in the ''Fire Festival 2019'', where he gained victories over Yuya Aoki, Asuka and [[Yuji Sakuragi|Super Tiger II]], but he was unable to win the tournament after a double countout with [[Yuji Hino]]. He looked to improve his odds in the ''Tenka-Ichi Junior Tournament 2019'', reaching the finals over Raicho and Sean Guiness, but being shockingly eliminated by Hub. This streak continued in the ''Furinkazan Tag Tournament 2019'', where Sugi and [[Dragon Gate (wrestling)|Dragon Gate]] representative [[Kenichiro Arai]] were defeated by [[Shuji Kondo]] and Takuya Sugawara in a match of former [[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon]] wrestlers.\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Michinoku Pro Wrestling]]'''\n:*[[Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n:*[[Tohoku Tag Team Championship]] ([[Tohoku Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Great Sasuke]]\n:*Fukumen World League Qualifying Tournament (2007)\n:*Futaritabi Tag Team League (2005) \u2013 with [[Fumiyuki Hashimoto|Kagetora]]\n:*M-12 Battle Royal (2006) <small>with Kagetora</small>\n\n*'''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''\n:*PWI ranked him #'''355''' of the 500 best singles wrestlers in the [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated|PWI 500]] in 2007\n\n*'''[[Pro Wrestling Zero1]]'''\n**[[International Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|International Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[International Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|1 time]])\n**[[NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|1 time]])\n:*[[NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Masamune (wrestler)|Masamune]]<ref name=Zero1010118>{{cite web | url = https://www.z-1.co.jp/topics/detail_625.html | script-title=ja:\u5c0f\u5e61\u304c\u4e16\u754c\u30d8\u30d3\u30fc\u3001\u5ca1\u672c\uff06\u5409\u6c5f\u306f\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u2015\u30b3\u30f3\u30c1\u7372\u5f97\u3001Sugi\u306f\u5165\u56e3\uff06\u653f\u5b97\u3068\u30e9\u30a4\u30c8\u30bf\u30c3\u30b0\u596a\u53d6\u3001\u30d6\u30fc\u30c9\u30a5\u306b\u6731\u5d07\u82b1\u52a0\u5165\u20261\u30fb1\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u30ea\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\uff01 | date=2018-01-01 | accessdate=2018-01-01 | work=[[Pro Wrestling Zero1]] | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n:*[[WWA World Junior Light Heavyweight Championship|WWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship ''(Disputed Branch)'']] ([[WWA World Junior Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])\n:*Tenka-Ichi Junior Tournament (2018)\n:*[[Furinkazan (wrestling)|Furinkazan]] ([[Furinkazan (wrestling)#2018|2018]]) \u2013 with [[Kohei Sato]]\n\n*'''[[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon X]]'''\n:*Yamaha Cup Tag Tournament (2004) \u2013 with [[Fumiyuki Hashimoto|SUWAcito]]\n\n*'''Valerie Office'''\n:*Copa El Jefe (2012) \u2013 with Argos\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Takuya Sugi}}\n*[http://luchalibreaaa.com/sugi-san.php AAA profile]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/el_blazer Takuya Sugi Myspace Fan Blog (English)]\n*[http://ameblo.jp/elblazer/ El Blazer official Blog (Japanese)]\n*[http://yoshitune.jugem.jp/ Yoshitsune official blog (Japanese)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061215012855/http://dgusa.puroresufan.com/doradodata.html El Dorado Roster Page at DGUSA (English)]\n*[http://www.puroresucentral.com/yoshitsune.html Yoshitsune profile at Puroresu Central (English)]\n*[http://www.michipro.net/ Michinoku Pro Wrestling official website (Japanese)]\n*[http://blog.livedoor.jp/dragon_door/archives/cat_50009189.html El Blazer El Dorado Blog (Japanese), no longer active]\n*[http://blogs.yahoo.co.jp/yumemaboroshi_nob_naga/ El Blazer official YAHOO Blog (Japanese), no longer active]\n{{Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sugi, Takuya}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Shizuoka (city)]]\n[[Category:Masked wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Shizuoka Prefecture]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name= Takuya Sugi\n|image= Sugi - Lucha Libre - Japan Expo 2011 - P1210485 Crop.jpg\n|caption= Sugi in July 2011\n|names= Sugi San<br>'''Sugi'''<br>El Blazer<br />Yoshitsune<br />Shanao<br />Mini Cima<br />Little Dragon <br />Hustle Kamen Ranger Red<br />Michinoku Ranger Gold<br />Ahii<br />The\u2605Zest (2nd generation)<br />Namazu Man<br />Rabbit Boy<br />Super Milo<br />Uwai #32<br />NOIZ<br />El Fuerte\n|height={{convert|1.63|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}<!-- In Japan they measure height in meters so that should be first -->\n|weight={{convert|65|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<!--In Japan they measure weight in kilograms so that should be first -->\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1983|10|6|mf=y}} \n|death_date = \n|birth_place = [[Shizuoka City]], Japan\n|resides=\n|billed= Hustle Nebula (as Hustle Kamen Ranger Red)<br />[[Hiraizumi, Iwate|Hiraizumi]] (as Shanao/Yoshitsune)\n|trainer=[[\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n]]<br />[[Jorge Rivera (wrestler)|Jorge \"Skayde\" Rivera]]\n|debut= May 11, 2003\n|retired=\n|}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Takuya Sugi'''|\u6749\u5353\u4e5f|Sugi Takuya}}<ref name=Puro>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresucentral.com/yoshitsune.html|title=Profile at Puroresu Central|publisher=Puroresu Central|accessdate=2012-01-15}}</ref> is a Japanese [[professional wrestler]] from [[Shizuoka City|Shizuoka]]. He is currently signed to [[Pro Wrestling Zero1]], where he works as '''Sugi''' (stylized in all capital letters). He has used many aliases, most commonly '''Yoshitsune''' and '''Sugi'''. He is mainly known for his high-flying abilities.\n\n==Career==\n===Toryumon (2002\u20132004)===\nImmediately after graduating in the 11th Toryumon school class term, Sugi debuted in 2003 in [[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon Mexico]], shortly after moving to the [[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon X]] brand. He went under the [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|gimmick]] of '''{{Nihongo|Mini Cima|\u30df\u30cbCIMA|Mini Cima}}''', a lighter version of the popular Toryumon wrestler [[Nobuhiko Oshima|Cima]], who was a part of the Mini Crazy Max [[Stable (professional wrestling)|stable]] along with [[Kagetora|Suwacito]] and [[Masaki Okimoto|Small Dandy Fuji]]. Aligning themselves as [[Tweener (professional wrestling)|tweeners]], they got into a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[BabyFace (professional wrestling)|babyface]] faction Sailor Boys ([[Taiji Ishimori]], [[Brahman Brothers|Kei Sato and Shu Sato]]), having several matches against them, sometimes accompanied by senior members of the actual Crazy Max.\n\nIn December 2003, Mini Cima and his team competed in the ''Young Dragons Cup 2003'' scramble match, but they were unable to win, being [[Takeshi Minamino]] the eventual tournament winner. They would be more successful at the ''Yamaha Cup 2004''tag team tournament, with Mini Cima and Suwacito defeating [[Manabu Murakami (wrestler)|Manabu Murakami]] and [[Naoki Tanizaki]] in the first round and the Sailor Boys in the second to crown themselves as winners. On September 9, 2003 the group competed in an elimination match for the [[UWA World Welterweight Championship]], eliminating the team of Los Carros Ex\u00f3ticos (Gallardo, Lambo Miura and Murcielago) before falling short to Los Salseros Japoneses (Minamino, [[Kenichi Sakai|Pineapple Hanai]] and [[Takayasu Fukuda|Mango Fukuda]]). This was the Toryumon X final event, with the promotion folding shortly after. Mini Crazy Max had its last reunion in the special event Dragon Fire The Final Challenge on October 14, where they competed in another special challenge match.\n\n===Hustle (2004\u20132006)===\nIn September 2004, still based on Toryumon, Sugi and his partners started wrestling for the [[Hustle (professional wrestling)|Hustle]] promotion. They appeared as the Hustle Kamen Rangers, a ''[[Power Rangers]]''-inspired [[super sentai]] stable which was a special division of the Hustle Army led by top babyface [[Naoya Ogawa]]. Sugi himself played '''{{Nihongo|Hustle Kamen Red|\u30cf\u30c3\u30b9\u30eb\u4eee\u9762\u30ec\u30c3\u30c9|Hassuru Kamen Reddo}}''' (a role formerly played by [[Masaki Okimoto]]), teaming up with [[Masaki Okimoto|Hustle Kamen Blue]] and [[Takayasu Fukuda|Hustle Kamen Yellow]] as a power trio. They competed in the undercard of events against villainous characters from the [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] Takada Monster Army commanded by [[Nobuhiko Takada|Generalissimo Takada]]; their usual opponents were [[Brahman Brothers|Devil Pierroth I & Devil Pierroth II]], whom they defeated in many occasions.\n\nIn the event Hustle House Vol.10, held on October 27, 2005, Hustle Kamen Rangers were defeated by [[Brahman Brothers|Demon Spider Blue, Demon Spider Yellow]] and [[Taiji Ishimori|Riser Glen]], being the latter in storyline a character come from the TV [[tokusatsu]] series ''Phantom Star God Justirisers'', only brainwashed to serve the Monster Army. In order to counter him, Hustle Kamen Rangers introduced another character from said series, [[Kota Ibushi|Liosazer]], who helped them to defeat the heel stable at the Hustlemania 2005 event and turn Riser again to good. The rangers would still competing for Hustle, being later opposed by an [[itako]] wrestler named Kyou Itako.\n\nOn February 10, 2006, the Monster Army introduced a cadre of [[Evil twin|evil clones]] of the Hustle Kamen Rangers, called the Monster Kamen Rangers. They consistently defeated Sugi and his team, forcing them to introduce a new member, [[Kota Ibushi|Hustle Kamen Orange]], in order to get the first win against the villains. The win was short-lived, however, as the Monster Kamen Rangers defeated them again, and this time kidnapped Hustle Kamen Yellow in order to [[brainwash]] him. Now with Yellow as an enemy, Red and new member Hustle Kamen Green attempted to reason with him, but they were beaten when Yellow pinned Red. The storyline continued until Hustlemania 2006, where they finally managed to bring Yellow back and defeat the Monster Kamen Rangers for good. The team then announced they would travel to the stars in order to defend the peace and justice beyond Hustle, ceasing their apparitions from the promotion.\n\n===Michinoku Pro Wrestling (2004\u20132009)===\nSugi started wrestling for [[Michinoku Pro Wrestling]] in October 2004. He debuted during the ''Futaritabi Tag Team Tournament 2004'' under the gimmick of '''{{Nihongo|Michinoku Ranger Gold|MICHINOKU \u30ec\u30f3\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc\u91d1|Michinoku Renj\u0101 Kin}}''', a super sentai character similar to the one he played in Hustle. Teaming up with [[Masaki Okimoto|Michinoku Ranger Silver]], Sugi got important victories over [[Jinsei Shinzaki]] and [[Shinjitsu Nohashi]] and Los Salseros Japoneses, but they did not win the league. They kept their gimmicks until December, when Sugi adopted the gimmick of '''{{Nihongo|Shanao|\u906e\u90a3\u738b|Shanao}}''', a masked [[Buddhist monk|monk]] inspired on the historical [[Minamoto no Yoshitsune]]. Shanao would come to the ring carrying a [[katana]] and saying prayers, and drew popularity among the audience for his high-risk, aerial style of wrestling.\n[[File:FUKUMEN-MANIA2018022048.jpg|thumb|240px|SUGI in 2019.]]\nIn 2005, Shanao joined forces with the Sailor Boys (now composed solely by Kei and Shu Sato) to participate in the ''Michinoku Trios League'', being unsuccessful. The final night of the tournament, in which they had been eliminated by points, Shanao teamed up with his master, [[Yoshihiro Asai|The Tiger II]], to defeat [[Fumiyuki Hashimoto|Kagetora]] and [[Shinjitsu Nohashi]]. The alliance with the Sailor Boys lasted until mid-year, when Shanao formed a tag team with [[Masaki Okimoto|Rasse]]. He also had a brief tenure in the ''Tetsujin Tournament'', but he was forced to forfeit most of his matches due to an injury. Shanao returned on September 10 in a losing effort to Takeshi Minamino, but he got his revenge the same night, defeating Minamino and Los Salseros Japoneses along with Kagetora, [[Kazuya Yuasa|Gaina]] and [[Hayato Fujita]].\n\nKagetora and he eventually kept their alliance and participated in the ''Futaritabi Tag Team Tournament 2005'', winning the league after beating Los Salseros Japoneses again, but Kagetora suddenly turned [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] and attacked Shanao, going to form the villainous stable Stoned. Now back with Rasse, Shanao and he had a shot for the [[Tohoku Tag Team Championship]] held by [[The Great Sasuke]] and [[Dick Togo]], but despite their effort, they were beaten. Days after, Shanao announced he was going to perform a [[genpuku]] ceremony in order to advance in his career, which was officiated by [[Jinsei Shinzaki]]. Shanao then changed his name to '''{{Nihongo|Yoshitsune|\u7fa9\u7d4c|Yoshitsune}}''', openly showing his identity, and changed his outfit to a [[samurai]]-like attire in purple, red and golden. Yoshitsune had his first match teaming up with Shinzaki, who came dressed as [[Sait\u014d Musashib\u014d Benkei]], defeating Rasse and Garuda with his new Shura finishing maneuver.\n\nThe next year, Yoshitsune's fame allowed him a title match for the [[Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship]] against [[Taka Michinoku]], falling short in his challenge. Nonetheless, Yoshitsune allied with The Great Sasuke and the now babyface Los Salseros Japoneses to wage war against Stoned, exchanging wins with them. He performed a new title pursuit by taking part in a tournament for the Tohoku Tag Team Championship with [[Tsutomu Oosugi|Rei]] as his partner, losing to [[Makoto Oishi]] and [[Shiori Asahi]]; Yoshitsune took part in the 2006 edition of the ''Tetsujin Tournament'', but he had to relinquish it again due to an injury. Upon his recovering, Yoshitsune recruited Rasse to compete in the ''Futaritabi Tag Team Tournament 2006'', but success seemed to be away from him that year, as they were eliminated at the finals by Kei and Shu Sato.\n\nIn 2007, Yoshitsune qualified for the ''Fukumen World League'' by defeating [[Kenichi Sakai|Ken45\u00ba]] and Shinjitsu Nohashi in respective matches. During the tournament, he eliminated [[Tatsuhito Senga|Shibaten]] first and legendary [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] member [[Jyushin Thunder Liger]] second, but he eventually fell to Mexican representative [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]] thanks to an intervention by Atlantis's cornerman Ol\u00edmpico. Ended the league, Yoshitsune returned to his alliance with the home army and joined The Great Sasuke for the ''Futaritabi Tag Team League''; although Sasuke and him eliminated the team of Rasse and Kagetora, an injury to Sasuke obliged them to exit the tournament and allow their opponents to advance round. Stardom finally came to Yoshitsune on November, however, when defeated [[Osaka Pro Wrestling]] representative Gaina in a match for the Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship. Yoshitsune then would open 2008 becoming a double champion, when Sasuke returned from his injury and joined him to defeat Rasse and Kagetora for the title.\n\nSugi retained his titles for most of 2008, beating challengers like Rasse, Takeshi Minamino, Shinji Nohashi and [[Tigers Mask]], as well as the team of [[Mens Teioh]] and [[Shinobu Sugawara|Shinobu]]. However, he would get in a new feud when [[Hayato Fujita]] turned heel and formed the faction Kowloon with the remnants of Stoned. After months of warfare, Hayato challenged Sugi to a match for the Tohoku Junior Heavyweight title, and he won the bout and the championship in an upset. Only months after, Sasuke and Yoshitsune faced Kei and Shu Sato from Kowloon in a match to unify their tag team titles with the [[UWA World Tag Team Championship]], but they were defeated and lost the belts. Concluded his reigns, Yoshitsune announced his departure from Michinoku Pro and had his last match in March 2009.\n\n===Dragondoor and El Dorado Wrestling (2005\u20132007)===\nAlong with most of his Toryumon class, Sugi joined the Dragondoor promotion in July 2005. He was introduced in a [[Vignette (professional wrestling)|vignette]] by top babyface Taiji Ishimori, who described him as a close ally carrying the genes of [[\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n]]. As such, Sugi appeared as '''{{Nihongo|Little Dragon|\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3|Ritoru Doragon}}''', a character wearing a mask and suit patterned after Drag\u00f3n, very much like the wrestler [[Dragon Kid]] from rival promotion [[Dragon Gate (wrestling)|Dragon Gate]]. In his first match, Little Dragon teamed up with Ishimori and the rest of his allies, [[Kota Ibushi]] and [[Tsutomu Oosugi|Milanito Collection a.t.]], in a losing effort against the popular stable Aagan Iisou ([[Shuji Kondo]], [[Yasushi Tsujimoto|Yasshi]] and [[Takuya Sugawara]]). His next and last high level match in the short-lived promotion would be at the final event, fighting with Ishimori against Stoned ([[Brahman Brothers|Kei Sato and Shu Sato]]), being defeated after an intervention by [[KAGETORA (wrestler)|Kagetora]] and [[Manabu Murakami (wrestler)|Maguro Ooma]]. Dragondoor closed shortly after.\n\nWhen the promotion was reopened as El Dorado Wrestling in April 2006, Sugi returned with the rest of wrestlers. This time he took the gimmick of '''{{Nihongo|El Blazer|\u30a8\u30eb\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30b6\u30fc|Eru Bureiz\u0101}}''', a mysterious, [[phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]]-like character in a gold and blue armored outfit. Blazer formed a tag team with Milanito Collection a.t. and took part in the very first match of the promotion, getting a victory over Kei and Shu Sato. They later avenged their defeats to Aagan Iisou by beating them with Kota Ibushi's aid, and also took another victory before Stoned in a [[Global Professional Wrestling Alliance]] event along with [[Jumping Kid Okimoto]]. In December 2006, the trio split up to compete in the ''Treasure Hunters Tag Tournament 2006'', with Ibushi teaming up with [[Milano Collection A.T.]] while Blazer stayed in Milanito's side; Sugi and his ally were defeated, and Milano and Kota advanced round before being eliminated by Dick Togo and Shuji Kondo at the finals. Milanito and Blazer, however, won the reserve bout of the tournament, defeating the Sato brothers through an intervention of a now unaligned Kagetora. In Sugi's last match in the promotion, he teamed up with Milano and Milanito to defeat a Stoned cell aided by [[Harashima]]. Blazer then announced he went freelance, and put an official end to his team with Milanito, leaving El Dorado.\n\n===All Japan Pro Wrestling (2006\u20132008)===\nOn August 20, 2006, Sugi made his first apparition in [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]] playing the character of '''Ahii''', the result of a cooperation between [[Sanrio|Sanrio Company Ltd.]] and AJPW. He was introduced by [[Keiji Mutoh]], and revealed himself as a strange character wearing a demonic-looking orange and black full body suit which represented the Mexican [[Habanero]] chili pepper. He made his first in-ring work the same night, entering after the main event to save Mutoh, [[Masanobu Fuchi]] and [[Kaz Hayashi]] from an attack by the [[Voodoo Murders]], and his official debut one day later, defeating VM member [[Fumiyuki Hashimoto|Voodoo Mask]]. Ahii remained as an ally to Mutoh and his babyface wrestlers against Voodoo Murders until November, when he got his own opponents in the form of [[Takayasu Fukuda|Mastodon]] and [[Takeshi Minamino|Tow Van John]], two personal enemies of his. Their enmity would be resolved on February 17, 2007, when Ahii defeated them both in a handicap match with the aid of his storyline brother, a green version of Ahii (played by [[Masaki Okimoto]]).\n\nSugi returned to AJPW on February 15, 2008 for a special event copromoted with [[Playboy]]. He played the one night gimmick of '''{{Nihongo|Rabbit Boy|\u30e9\u30d3\u30c3\u30c8\u30fb\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4|Rabitto B\u014di}}''', a character wearing a [[rabbit]] mask and a black playboy jacket. In his only apparition, Rabbit Boy defeated [[Masaki Okimoto|Giant Jet]].\n\nOn December 23, Sugi made his last apparition for AJPW for another one night character, this time as part of AJPW's usual copromotions with [[A Bathing Ape]]. Sugi portrayed '''Super Milo''', a [[monkey]] [[superhero]] wearing in green and yellow, and teamed up with [[Mitsunobu Kikuzawa|Teriyaki Boy]] to defeat Ebessan III and [[Kuishinbo Kamen]] in a comedy match.\n\n===Independent circuit (2006\u20132009)===\n[[File:FUKUMEN-MANIA2018022152.jpg|thumb|240px|SUGI along with Mr. Cacao (center) and El Hornet (right) in 2019.]]\nHe also appeared as Yoshitsune in some shows of Big Mouth LOUD and several others Japanese independent promotions, including the [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] LOCK UP sub-brand.\n\nSugi continued using the El Blazer gimmick as his main freelancing character. El Blazer then turned to a comedic character prone to mysteriously faint at his entrance, and had an appearance in [[Dramatic Dream Team]]'s brand ''Cruiser's Game'' wrestling against [[Kyohei Mikami|Mikami]] after ([[kayfabe]]) having been smoking [[marijuana]].\n\nSoon after becoming a freelancer, Sugi continued appearing randomly in several Japanese promotions as El Blazer, including [[Inoki Genome Federation|IGF]].\n\nStarting from June 3, 2007, Sugi appears in [[Kensuke Office]] as '''Namazu Man''' (\u306a\u307e\u305a\u30de\u30f3, \"Catfish Man\"). Shortly after, Namazu Man started to be played by another wrestler.\n\nAnother gimmick he used in 2007 is '''UWAI # 32''', a robot character only used in UWAI Station.\n\nOn December 29, 2008, Sugi appeared in an Akiba Pro Wrestling event as '''El Fuerte''' (\u30a8\u30eb\u30fb\u30d5\u30a9\u30eb\u30c6), a character inspired from the [[Street Fighter (video game)|Street Fighter]] video game saga.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.famitsu.com/game/news/1221018_1124.html | script-title=ja:\u30bd\u30ea\u30c3\u30c9\u30fb\u30b9\u30cd\u30fc\u30af\u304c\u7121\u7dda\u3067\u6307\u793a\uff01\uff1f \u30a2\u30ad\u30d0\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u7b2c2\u5f3e\u201c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30ea\u30df\u30c3\u30af\u30b9 \u6e7e\u5cb8\u6709\u660e\u5371\u6a5f\u4e00\u9aea\uff01\u201d\u304c\u958b\u50ac | date=2008-12-29 | accessdate=2016-10-04 |work=Famitsu.com | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n===Pro Wrestling Zero1 (2007\u20132009)===\nSugi started wrestling for [[Pro Wrestling Zero1-Max]] in May 2007 under his El Blazer character. After an unsuccessful battle royal match for the [[AWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship]], which was won by [[Dick Togo]], Blazer aligned himself under [[Masato Tanaka]]'s Sword Army, getting in battles against [[Takao Omori]]'s Axe Army. He got a shot at the [[ZERO1-MAX International Junior Heavyweight Championship]] held by Dragon Gate wrestler [[Masaaki Mochizuki]], but he was unsuccessful. Mochizuki offered him to team up and invited him to his promotion.\n\nFor most of his tenure in the company, however, Sugi ditched his Blazer identity and played a new character, '''The\u2606ZEST''', sponsored by the homonymous Japanese [[pachinko]] company. The gimmick had been played before by the wrestler Kamikaze, and would be played again by him later. On July 24, Zest won the WWA Junior Lightweight Championship by beating Osamu Namiguchi, and retained him until April 6, when Sugi relinquished both the character and the title and adopted yet a new gimmick, '''Noiz''', sponsored by rock band [[UchuSentai:Noiz]]. Now as Noiz, Sugi defeated Kamikaze as Zest and won again the championship. NOIZ also inherited Blazer's loyalty to Masato Tanaka, wrestling for him occasionally, and retained the title before Osamu Namiguchi before vacating him upon his departure from Zero1.\n\n===Dragon Gate (2008)===\nBlazer originally debuted in Dragon Gate on March 2008 as a Zero1 representative, but he was in storyline recognized by [[Kenichiro Arai]] as a Toryumon graduate. Blazer's first match was a special tag team with [[Ben Satterly|Pac]] against Tozawa-juku (Arai and [[Taku Iwasa]]), but he also aided New Hazard ([[BxB Hulk]] and [[Shinobu Sugawara|Shinobu]]) in the Mochizuki Buyuden events and Typhoon ([[Anthony W. Mori]] and [[Cima (wrestler)|Cima]]) against the [[Muscle Outlaw'z]]. In April, Blazer took part in a tournament for the [[Open the Brave Gate Championship]], eliminating Genki Horiguchi but being eliminated himself by [[Gamma (wrestler)|Gamma]] following outside interference. After his unsuccessful feud with Muscle Outlaw'z, Blazer concluded his tenure in Dragon Gate forming an alliance with fellow outsiders [[Takeshi Minamino]] and [[Shinjitsu Nohashi]], defeating [[Hayato Fujita]], [[Munenori Sawa]] and Yuta Yoshikawa in Mochizuki Buyuden and WORLD-1 ([[Kzy|mcKZ]] & [[Naoki Tanizaki]]) & Super Shenlong in Dragon Gate NEX.\n\n===Pro Wrestling Guerrilla (2008)===\nSugi made his [[United States|America]]n debut (as El Blazer) for [[Pro Wrestling Guerrilla]] on May 17, 2008. Replacing [[Kota Ibushi]], he teamed with Kagetora on PWG's second annual ''DDT4'' tournament, defeating [[Scott Lost]] and [[Joey Ryan (wrestler)|Joey Ryan]] in the first round, but losing to the [[PWG World Tag Team Championship|PWG World Tag Team Champions]] [[Kevin Steen and El Generico]] in a title match in the next.\n\n===Lucha Libre AAA World Wide (2009\u20132012)===\nSugi signed up with [[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide]] in 2009 and made his return to M\u00e9xico, now under a modified, black and red version of his Yoshitsune outfit and the name of '''Sugi San''' (his last name followed by the [[Japanese honorifics|Japanese honorific -san]]). He was introduced by [[Kenzo Suzuki]] as a part of his [[heel (professional wrestling)|rudo]] stable La Yakuza, thus turning Sugi heel for the first time in his career. The faction, which also included [[El Oriental]], amassed a number of tag team wins until a match in [[Verano de Esc\u00e1ndalo (2009)|Verano de Esc\u00e1ndalo]], where they fell to [[The Psycho Circus]]. On August 30, Sugi competed individually in a [[Steel Cage Match]] where the last wrestler would be fired; Sugi escaped safely, but he got injured upon doing a theatrical backflip from the cage to the floor.\n[[File:Sugi.jpg|thumb|250px|Sugi in an AAA event.]]\nA month later, with La Yakuza dissolved and now unaligned, Sugi competed in a Five Way Ladder Match for the [[AAA World Cruiserweight Championship]] along with [[Extreme Tiger]], [[Jack Evans (wrestler)|Jack Evans]], [[Rocky Romero]] and [[Teddy Hart]], but he would be (kayfabe) injured by a piledriver by Hart and had to be stretchered out while Tiger won the title. After his return from the injury, Sugi took part in the ''Torneo Alas de Oro 2009'', leaving in second place along with [[Billy Boy]]. On October 9, Suzuki gathered La Yakuza again with [[Go Shiozaki]] replacing El Oriental to face Los Wagner Maniacos ([[Dr. Wagner Jr.]], [[Electroshock (wrestler)|Electroshock]] & [[\u00daltimo Gladiador]]), but they were defeated. Afterwards, Sugi announced his return to Japan, leaving AAA.\n\nAfter a year of hiatus, Sugi would compete in [[Pro Wrestling Noah]] as an AAA representative, now under the name of '''Sugi''' (in all caps), getting in a feud with [[Tatsuhito Senga|Ronin]] and [[Taiji Ishimori]]. He returned to M\u00e9xico along with Ronin, having touring matches against him, and finally coming back to TV as an unofficial member of [[Aero Star]]'s stable [[Real Fuerza Aerea]]. On June 28, Sugi and Ronin were sent to [[Paris, France]] in order to represent [[puroresu]] in the [[Japan Expo|Japan Expo 12th Impact]], returning to M\u00e9xico on July 5.\n\nOn July 9, 2012, Sugi held a press conference to announce his involvement in a conspiracy that had gotten [[Kazushige Nosawa]] and [[Io Shirai]] arrested for marijuana possession and smuggling. According to Sugi, Masahiro Hayashi, who worked as a liaison between AAA and Japan and had a personal grudge with Nosawa, promised him a contract extension with AAA in exchange for him planting the drugs on the couple.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://superluchas.com/sugi-san-confiesa-complot-en-contra-de-nosawa/ | title = Sugi San confiesa complot en contra de Nosawa. | author=Dark Angelita | date=2012-07-10 | accessdate=2012-07-10 | publisher=[[Super Luchas]] Magazine | language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Michinoku Pro Wrestling (2016)===\nFollowing the drug smuggling scandal, Sugi remained inactive for more than four years, with the exception of a single match held on November 18, 2015, when he faced [[Takeshi Minamino]] in an event held at [[Shinjuku Face]] to celebrate the 10th anniversary since his debut.\nAfter this long hiatus, Sugi returned to the ring for a charity event held on August 28, 2016, in support of the population hit by the [[2016 Kumamoto earthquakes|2016 Kumamoto earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://lineblog.me/mentaikid/archives/9986865.html | script-title=ja:\u30b9\u30bf\u30a4\u30eb\uff01 | date=2016-08-29 | accessdate=2016-10-06 |work=Mentai Kid Blog | language=Japanese}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, on September 16, he competed in a Michinoku Pro event for the first time in seven years, entering the 2016 Fukumen World League.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://battle-news.com/?p=23839 | script-title=ja:\u30ab\u30ea\u30b9\u30c6\u30a3\u30b3\uff08\u521d\u4ee3\u30df\u30b9\u30c6\u30a3\u30b3\uff09\u304c\u307f\u3061\u306e\u304f\u306e\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u306b\u51f1\u65cb\uff014\u5e74\u524d\u306e\u4e0d\u7965\u4e8b\u3067\u6d3b\u52d5\u3092\u4f11\u6b62\u3057\u3066\u3044\u305fSugi\u304c\u5fa9\u6d3b\uff01 | date=2016-09-17 | accessdate=2016-09-17 |work=Battle News | language=Japanese}}</ref> He defeated Leprechaun and Eisa8, but was eliminated by [[Car\u00edstico]] at the semi-finals.\n\n===Return to Zero1 (2017\u2013present)===\nAfter a few appearances in Pro Wrestling Land's End in 2017, Sugi returned to [[Pro Wrestling Zero1]] in August. He challenged unsuccessfully [[Kotaro Suzuki]] for the [[International Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|International Junior Heavyweight]] and [[NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship]]s, after which he declared he would challenge [[Ikuto Hidaka]] and [[Takuya Sugawara]] for the [[NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship]] with an unknown partner, which would revealed to be [[Psycho (wrestler)|Psycho]]. Sugi and him defeated Hidaka and Sugawara in a non-title match, but failed at taking the titles. Sugi replaced Psycho by Sean Guinness for the ''Furinkazan Tag Tournament 2017'', only to be eliminated in the first round by Hidaka and Sugawara again. He spent the next weeks teaming with several wrestlers against his old enemy faction [[Voodoo Murders]], until he announced [[Masamune (wrestler)|Masamune]] as his next tag team partner in his quest for the tag titles. On January 1, 2018, Sugi officially joined Zero1,<ref name=Zero1010118/> and the same day, he and Masamune won the NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship from Sugawara and Hidaka.<ref name=Zero1010118/>\n[[File:FUKUMEN-MANIA2018022147.jpg|thumb|250px|SUGI at the Fukumen Mania 2019.]]\nTheir reign ended in June, when Sugi and Masamune lost the titles to the new team of Ikuto Hidaka and Fuminori Abe. The same month, Sugi joined [[Kohei Sato]] and challenged [[Masato Tanaka]] and [[Yuji Hino]] for the [[NWA Intercontinental Tag Team Championship]], but they were defeated. He followed with a significantly successful tenure in the ''Fire Festival 2018'', scoring wins over Hino, [[Shinjiro Otani]] and [[Hiroshi Yamato]], though victory escaped his grasp again. In November, Sugi would prove better in the short ''Tenka-Ichi Junior Tournament 2018'' for the vacated [[International Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|International Junior Heavyweight Championship]] and [[NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship]], winning the tournament and the titles after beating [[Tatsuhito Takaiwa]], Asuka and [[Hayata (wrestler)|Hayata]]. Now as a champion, he resumed his team Kohei Sato to compete in the ''Furinkazan Tag Tournament 2018'', where they also won by defeating Chris Vice and [[Shogun Okamoto]] at the finals.\n\nSugi invested early 2019 in further championship pursuings. He retained his singles titles against Ikuto Hidaka, Shoki Kitamura and [[Tatsuhito Takaiwa]]. However, tag team titles remained away from him, with two failed challenges for the NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championships and NWA Intercontinental Tag Team Championships teaming up with [[Madoka (wrestler)|Hagane Shinnou]] and usual partner Sato respectively. In July, he participated in the ''Fire Festival 2019'', where he gained victories over Yuya Aoki, Asuka and [[Yuji Sakuragi|Super Tiger II]], but he was unable to win the tournament after a double countout with [[Yuji Hino]]. He looked to improve his odds in the ''Tenka-Ichi Junior Tournament 2019'', reaching the finals over Raicho and Sean Guiness, but being shockingly eliminated by Hub. This streak continued in the ''Furinkazan Tag Tournament 2019'', where Sugi and [[Dragon Gate (wrestling)|Dragon Gate]] representative [[Kenichiro Arai]] were defeated by [[Shuji Kondo]] and Takuya Sugawara in a match of former [[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon]] wrestlers.\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Michinoku Pro Wrestling]]'''\n:*[[Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n:*[[Tohoku Tag Team Championship]] ([[Tohoku Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Great Sasuke]]\n:*Fukumen World League Qualifying Tournament (2007)\n:*Futaritabi Tag Team League (2005) \u2013 with [[Fumiyuki Hashimoto|Kagetora]]\n:*M-12 Battle Royal (2006) <small>with Kagetora</small>\n\n*'''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''\n:*PWI ranked him #'''355''' of the 500 best singles wrestlers in the [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated|PWI 500]] in 2007\n\n*'''[[Pro Wrestling Zero1]]'''\n**[[International Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|International Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[International Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|1 time]])\n**[[NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship (Zero1)|1 time]])\n:*[[NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA International Lightweight Tag Team Championship|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Masamune (wrestler)|Masamune]]<ref name=Zero1010118>{{cite web | url = https://www.z-1.co.jp/topics/detail_625.html | script-title=ja:\u5c0f\u5e61\u304c\u4e16\u754c\u30d8\u30d3\u30fc\u3001\u5ca1\u672c\uff06\u5409\u6c5f\u306f\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u2015\u30b3\u30f3\u30c1\u7372\u5f97\u3001Sugi\u306f\u5165\u56e3\uff06\u653f\u5b97\u3068\u30e9\u30a4\u30c8\u30bf\u30c3\u30b0\u596a\u53d6\u3001\u30d6\u30fc\u30c9\u30a5\u306b\u6731\u5d07\u82b1\u52a0\u5165\u20261\u30fb1\u5f8c\u697d\u5712\u30ea\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\uff01 | date=2018-01-01 | accessdate=2018-01-01 | work=[[Pro Wrestling Zero1]] | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n:*[[WWA World Junior Light Heavyweight Championship|WWA World Junior Heavyweight Championship ''(Disputed Branch)'']] ([[WWA World Junior Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])\n:*Tenka-Ichi Junior Tournament (2018)\n:*[[Furinkazan (wrestling)|Furinkazan]] ([[Furinkazan (wrestling)#2018|2018]]) \u2013 with [[Kohei Sato]]\n\n*'''[[Toryumon (\u00daltimo Drag\u00f3n)|Toryumon X]]'''\n:*Yamaha Cup Tag Tournament (2004) \u2013 with [[Fumiyuki Hashimoto|SUWAcito]]\n\n*'''Valerie Office'''\n:*Copa El Jefe (2012) \u2013 with Argos\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Takuya Sugi}}\n*[http://luchalibreaaa.com/sugi-san.php AAA profile]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/el_blazer Takuya Sugi Myspace Fan Blog (English)]\n*[http://ameblo.jp/elblazer/ El Blazer official Blog (Japanese)]\n*[http://yoshitune.jugem.jp/ Yoshitsune official blog (Japanese)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061215012855/http://dgusa.puroresufan.com/doradodata.html El Dorado Roster Page at DGUSA (English)]\n*[http://www.puroresucentral.com/yoshitsune.html Yoshitsune profile at Puroresu Central (English)]\n*[http://www.michipro.net/ Michinoku Pro Wrestling official website (Japanese)]\n*[http://blog.livedoor.jp/dragon_door/archives/cat_50009189.html El Blazer El Dorado Blog (Japanese), no longer active]\n*[http://blogs.yahoo.co.jp/yumemaboroshi_nob_naga/ El Blazer official YAHOO Blog (Japanese), no longer active]\n{{Tohoku Junior Heavyweight Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sugi, Takuya}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Shizuoka (city)]]\n[[Category:Masked wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Shizuoka Prefecture]]\n", "name_user": "2601:80:4105:cc30:1484:a830:918b:8c92", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Takuya_Sugi"}
{"title_page": "60th British Academy Film Awards", "text_new": "{{Infobox film awards\n| number            = 60\n| award             = British Academy Film Awards\n| date              = 11 February 2007\n| site              = [[Royal Opera House|Royal Opera House, Covent Garden]], [[London]]\n| host              = [[Jonathan Ross]]\n| producer          = \n| director          = \n| best_film         = '''''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]'''''\n| best_british      = '''''[[The Last King of Scotland (film)|The Last King of Scotland]]'''''\n| best_actor        = '''[[Forest Whitaker]]'''\n| best_actor_film   = ''[[The Last King of Scotland (film)|The Last King of Scotland]]''\n| best_actress      = '''[[Helen Mirren]]'''\n| best_actress_film = ''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]''\n| most_wins         = '''''[[The Last King of Scotland (film)|The Last King of Scotland]]'' and ''[[Pan's Labyrinth|Pan's Labyrinth (El laberinto del fauno)]]''''' (3; tied)\n| most_nominations  = '''''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]''''' (9)\n| channel           = \n| duration          = \n| ratings           = \n| last              = 59th\n| next              = 61st\n}}\n\nThe '''60th [[British Academy Film Awards]]''', given by the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]], took place on 11 February 2007 and honoured the best films of [[2006 in film|2006]].\n\n''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]'' won [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]] and Best Actress for [[Helen Mirren]]. [[Paul Greengrass]] won Best Director for ''[[United 93 (film)|United 93]]'', which also won Best Editing. [[Forest Whitaker]] won Best Actor for ''[[The Last King of Scotland (film)|The Last King of Scotland]]'', which also won Outstanding British Film and Best Adapted Screenplay. The ceremony also featured the inaugural [[BAFTA Award for Best Animated Film]], which was awarded to ''[[Happy Feet]]'', directed by [[George Miller (director)|George Miller]].\n\n==Winners and nominees==\n[[File:Bourne 3 Premiere Greengrass.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Paul Greengrass]], Best Director winner]]\n[[File:Forest Whitaker 2014.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Forest Whitaker]], Best Actor in a Leading Role winner]]\n[[File:Helen Mirren 2014.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Helen Mirren]], Best Actress in a Leading Role winner]]\n[[File:AlanArkinTIFFSept2012.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Alan Arkin]], Best Actor in a Supporting Role winner]]\n[[File:Jennifer-Hudson 2012-01-17 Barnes-Noble Chicago photoby Adam-Bielawski (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Jennifer Hudson]], Best Actress in a Supporting Role winner]]\n[[File:Michael Arndt, 2007.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Michael Arndt]], Best Original Screenplay winner]]\n[[File:Peter Morgan 2010.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Peter Morgan]], Best Adapted Screenplay co-winner]]\n[[File:EvaGreenFeb07.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Eva Green]], Rising Star Award winner]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#BDB76B; width: 50%\" | [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n! style=\"background:#BDB76B; width: 50%\" | [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]'''''\n* ''[[Babel (film)|Babel]]''\n* ''[[The Departed]]''\n* ''[[The Last King of Scotland (film)|The Last King of Scotland]]''\n* ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''[[Paul Greengrass]] \u2013 ''[[United 93 (film)|United 93]]'''''\n* [[Jonathan Dayton and Valerie Faris]] \u2013 ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]''\n* [[Stephen Frears]] \u2013 ''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]''\n* [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]] \u2013 ''[[Babel (film)|Babel]]''\n* [[Martin Scorsese]] \u2013 ''[[The Departed]]''\n|-\n! style=\"background:#BDB76B;\" | [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]\n! style=\"background:#BDB76B;\" | [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress in a Leading Role]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''[[Forest Whitaker]] \u2013 ''[[The Last 